<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Prime Minister Appointed in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 10 (Xinhua) -- King of Nepal Birendra today
appointed Lokendra Bahadur Chand as prime minister of a new
coalition government which is to replace the outgoing one led by
Sher Bahadur Deuba, the royal palace announced here this evening.
</P>
<P>
Chand, parliamentary leader of the National Democratic Party
(RPP), submitted to the king a petition earlier in the day for
forming a four-party government by claiming majority support in
the 205-seat lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
The new ruling coalition is expected to comprise Chand's RPP
party, the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist,
CPN-UML), the Nepal Goodwill Party (NSP) and the Nepal Workers and
Peasants' Party (NWPP), sources said.
</P>
<P>
The RPP and the NSP had been ruling partners of the outgoing
government led by Deuba's Nepali Congress (NC) party.
</P>
<P>
The Deuba government resigned last Thursday after losing a
confidence vote in the lower house.
</P>
<P>
Chand, 57, a two-time prime minister during the partyless
Panchayat legislature which ended in 1990, has played a crucial
role in bringing down the Deuba government.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of an RPP faction led by Chand and the NSP party
from the NC-led coalition resulted in Thursday's defeat in a
confidence motion tabled by Deuba in parliament for his
government.
</P>
<P>
The former main opposition the CPN-UML, with its 90 MPs in the
house, will demand vice-prime ministership and other important
posts in Chand's cabinet, which is expected to be announced
Tuesday, sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
