<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Senate Chairman Meets U.S. Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Senate leader Wasim
Sajjad said today that Pakistan is striving to improve its
economic situation, promote privatization and boost a liberal
market economy.
</P>
<P>
Sajjad made the remarks during a meeting here with a
nine-member delegation of the U.S. Council of Foreign Relations.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan was also striving to improve the law and order
situation and foster good relations with all countries, the
neighboring states in particular.
</P>
<P>
A number of crucial economic measures were being worked out by
the government with a view to bailing the country out of the
difficult economic situation, said Sajjad.
</P>
<P>
He said the government enjoyed the trust of the business
community, and expressed the hope that Pakistan's economy would
pick up soon.
</P>
<P>
The Senate leader asked the U.S. corporate sector to invest in
Pakistan, promising that impediments to foreign investments would
be removed.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan would like to resolve all bilateral issues peacefully
and was prepared to hold discussions with India on all contentious
issues, including Jammu and Kashmir, so as to arrive at a peaceful
negotiated settlement of the core issues, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that resolution of the disputes would provide the
necessary impetus for peace, security and development in South
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Sajjad expressed the hope that the visit by the US delegation
would lead to a better understanding of the domestic situation in
Pakistan and more investment opportunities that the Pakistani
Government wants to extend to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the delegation, Maurice Greenberg, said that
peace in the region would automatically help in attracting foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan needed to build infrastructure and increase
the domestic savings rate which is believed to be too low.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
