<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Reimposes Minimum Prices on Computer Chips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) today
reimposed minimum prices on DRAMs which originate in Japan and
South Korea and are sold in the EU, but companies will not be
obliged to raise their prices during March.
</P>
<P>
The EU imposed 60-percent anti-dumping duties on DRAMs from
Japan in January 1990 and 24.7-percent anti-dumping duties on
South Korean-made DRAMs in March 1993, after Japanese and South
Korean exporters were accused of dumping on EU markets.
</P>
<P>
But these measures were suspended 21 months ago following a
price rise in DRAMs.
</P>
<P>
The EU reintroduced the anti-dumping measures on the ground
that prices of most DRAM products have fallen below the production
cost and EU DRAM producers are suffering losses.
</P>
<P>
However, the European Commission decided to carry out those
measures in a flexible, gradual way in order to minimize the
potential risks of destabilizing the DRAM market, until an overall
review of anti-dumping restrictions is completed in June this year.
</P>
<P>
A commission spokesman said that the EU has informed Japanese
and South Korean exporters of its latest decision in the form of a
memorandum of understanding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
