<HEADLINE> Mubarak: US Loses Credibility With UN Veto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak has expressed his regret that the United States should
have vetoed a U.N. Security Council's resolution to condemn
Israel's decision to build a Jewish neighborhood in the Arab
residential areas of east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president was speaking on the eve of his meeting
with U.S. President Bill Clinton this morning.
</P>
<P>
"It's unfortunate that the veto should have been adopted by the
United States. Without the veto, it could have given a signal to
the Israelis not to go through violating the agreements (between
the Israelis and Palestinians), not to create problems for the
peace process," Mubarak told the CNN "Late Edition" program in an
interview Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States has lost credibility as an honest
broker among the Arabs by its move against the U.N. Security
Council's resolution.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab world have an idea that the United States is a fair
partner in the peace process. But I think with the veto, I think
it will create much more -- a feeling of injustice from the United
States," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. veto in the U.N. Security Council has contradicted
Clinton's remarks when he said the Israeli housing plan could only
"build mistrust" during his meeting with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat last Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said he would ask Clinton to pressure Israel to reverse
its decision to build 6,500 homes in east Jerusalem, which was
captured by Israel during the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to ask President Clinton to take his influence,
to use his influence with the Israelis to just stop this," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak warned Israel that its handling of the thorny issue of
Jewish settlement in east Jerusalem without consulting with the
Palestinians may explode the whole peace process in the Middle
East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
