<HEADLINE> Tobacco Auctions Ready in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Preparations for the opening of
Zimbabwe's flue-cured tobacco auctions are progressing well
despite concern that this year's crop could be well below
farmers' expectations.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe Tobacco Association Public Relations Director Lal
Taylor today said that farmers are busy making preparations for
this year's auction floors which are expected to open on April 22
and run until mid-October.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco farmers are this year expected to deliver between 215
million and 220 million kilograms, up from about 201 million kg
last year which earned the country about 527 million U.S. Dollars
in foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
Taylor noted that due to heavy rains this season, the
country's tobacco farmers had been forced to down-size their crop
projections from the initial estimates of between 235 million to
240 million kg.
</P>
<P>
''Fortunately the quality of the crop has not suffered and all
indications show there will be increased demand this year,'' she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
