<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Russia to Continue Nuclear Cooperation: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Indian External Affairs
Minister Inder Kumar Gujral said today that India and Russia will
continue cooperation to build a nuclear power station in India.
</P>
<P>
In reply to a question in the lower house of the Indian
parliament here, Gujral said that Moscow has not changed its mind
in helping India build the Kudankulam nuclear power station after
Russian Prime Minister Victor Chernomyrdin's visit to the United
States, which has reportedly pressured Russia not to help India
with the nuclear power project.
</P>
<P>
A cooperation agreement to help India build a nuclear power
station was signed in 1988, but its implementation was delayed due
to political changes in the erstwhile Soviet Union, Gujral said.
</P>
<P>
This particular advanced technology for setting up a
1,000-megawatt nuclear power station is not available with Indian
scientists, who are keen to go ahead with it, added the minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
