<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conservatives Will Win General Election: John Major </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- British ruling Conservative Party
leader John Major said here today the conservatives were behind in
1992 but came back to win.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Talk Radio, Prime Minister John Major said Britain
was outperforming its European Union partners with lower inflation
and lower unemployment.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the Labor Party for offering lightweight
policies. "This is not a country where you can deal with long-term
problems with short-term snappy solutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Major, who has faced severe problems in uniting his party over
Europe, insisted that calls from right-wingers such as MP Sir
George Gardiner for him to rule out British membership of a single
European currency were not in the country's interests.
</P>
<P>
He repeated his view that the time had not yet come to decide
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
However, he said he would be prepared to use Britain's EU vote
to stop countries joining a single currency if their economies
were not ready for it.
</P>
<P>
"If they were likely to go ahead in the wrong circumstances, it
is in the British national interest to stop them doing so," Major
said.
</P>
<P>
If a single currency were "botched" without Britain joining
it, the pound sterling could rise sharply against it. "That would
make all our exporters uncompetitive," Major said.
</P>
<P>
With a general election expected in May, Major's Conservatives
were staggered by right-wing MP Sir George Gardiner's decision to
join the Referendum Party last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It has pushed Major into a two-seat minority in parliament and
play its part in putting the Conservatives some 20 points behind
Labor in the opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
Major dismissed the group Gardiner has joined as "a one-issue
party with a remarkably shortsighted view." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
