<HEADLINE> Board to Look Into Zimbabwe's Reserve Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 10 (Xinhua) -- A board comprising military
experts has been set up to look into the intricacies of forming
the envisaged national reserve defense force to be called up
during war emergencies.
</P>
<P>
defence minister moven mahachi announced formation of the
reserve force late last year, saying a 9.09 million U.S. Dollars
fund had been set up to equip the force which will comprise
retired soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Forces Headquarters of Zimbabwe said today in a
statement, ''the board is now complete. An announcement will be
made in due course once the findings and recommendations have
been approved by the authorities.''
</P>
<P>
Formation of the reserve force comes at a time when the
Zimbabwean army is trimming its force from 51,000 to a manageable
40,000-strong one in line with international trends of cutting
defense budgets.
</P>
<P>
Major-General Paradzai Zimonte has already been appointed the
Chief of Staff of the Reserve Force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
