<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Satisfied Over Agreement to End Crisis in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Greece has expressed its
satisfaction over an agreement reached between Albanian President
Sali Berisha and his political opponents to end the crisis in
Albania and pledged support in efforts to complete the nine-point
deal.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said in a statement
today that Prime Minister Costas Simitis telephoned Berisha Sunday
night to express "his satisfaction over the reaching of the
agreement."
</P>
<P>
The nine-point agreement, signed Sunday after two days of talks
and mediation by top European envoys, called for the formation of
an interim all-party government to supervise general elections to
be held in June.
</P>
<P>
Reppas said the Greek premier also "stressed the need for the
completion of all steps in finding a final solution and assured
Berisha of Greece's support in the efforts of the people of
Albania to achieve progress, development and democracy."
</P>
<P>
Reppas described the agreement as a "positive development" and
expressed the conviction that "Albania's political forces will
make every effort to lead the country out of the present crisis
through political consensus and peaceful procedures."
</P>
<P>
According to him, Greece is concerned over the situation in the
neighboring country, fearing that the crisis will harm the
interests of the ethnic Greeks, lead to the influx of large
numbers of refugees and destabilize the peace in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
