<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renault Workers to Stage Protest in Paris Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 10 (Xinhua) -- French unionists said today that
8,000 to 10,000 European workers of the Renault automaker will
stage a protest in Paris Tuesday against the auto group's decision
to close its assembly plant in Vilvoorde, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators will gather outside the Renault headquarters
in Billancourt, west of Paris, and will march around its outskirts
before organizing a "European picnic," while the committee of
European group of Renault is holding an extraordinary session at
Boulogne-Billancourt.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian, French and Spanish unionists are calling for the
"obtaining of real negotiations and annulation of the measures
taken" to close the plant, which they described as "unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted the unionists as saying
that "alternative solutions exist for industrial policy and
significant reduction of working hours" to avoid the closure of
the Vilvoorde plant and other layoffs.
</P>
<P>
They also called on Renault's leadership, the European
Community and the public powers of Belgium and France to change
their attitude.
</P>
<P>
The committee of European group of Renault, which is a purely
consultative organ gathering representatives of workers from the
Renault headquarters and its branches in Europe, will discuss
"evaluation and perspective of the strategy of Renault" and the
"motivation of cessation of activity of the Vilvoorde plant and
its consequences on employment."
</P>
<P>
But it is little probable that the committee will start Tuesday
negotiations with the president of Renault, Louis Schweitzer, said
AFP.
</P>
<P>
AFP said that the unionists are trying to gather enough force
from all the European plants of Renault to pressure the leadership
to step back on its decision, before starting deep-touched
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The workers of Renault plants in France, Belgium and Spain
staged a one-hour strike last Thursday to protest the closure of
the Vilvoorde plant, which will result in the layoff of 3,100
workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
