<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Brushes Aside Arafat's Warning of Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu today brushed aside the warning issued by
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat that
the peace process was in "real crisis."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu held consultations with coalition members on
coalition crisis and the mounting tension with the Palestinian
side before departing for a two-day visit to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Arafat's warning, Netanyahu said that the
Palestinians now finally realized that a new national government
had taken office in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli leader said the message had been conveyed to
the Palestinian side by Foreign Minister David Levy during his
Sunday night's meeting with Arafat's deputy Mahmoud Abbas (Abu
Mazen) and other Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
Abbas today offered resignation to Arafat to protest over
what he described as Israel's continued violation of the
signed peace accords. Arafat has yet accepted his resignation.
</P>
<P>
Levy rejected the Palestinian protests over Israel's decision
on the first stage of troop pullbacks, its plan to build
Har Homa neighborhood in southeastern Jerusalem, and its order
to close four Palestinian offices in eastern Jerusalem. Levy
stressed that Israel would proceed with construction in Har
Homa despite the PNA's strong opposition.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu repeated that the Arab world would understand that
his government would stand firm behind all interests of
Israel.
</P>
<P>
PNA Secretary Ahmed abdel Rahman attacked Israel for "freezing
everything." He warned that the PNA was ready to freeze the
peace process if Israel continued violating the peace accords.
</P>
<P>
In another angry reaction, Palestinian Council
Speaker Ahmed Qreia (Abu Ala) today demanded suspension of
peace talks with Israel. He also called for international
examination of further implementation of the Israeli-Palestinian
interim agreement. But international intervention needs agreement
from both sides.
</P>
<P>
The PNA is increasingly angry with a series of hardline
moves taken by Israel, including the decision on pulling back
troops from only 9 percent of the West Bank in the first
stage, the plan to build the Har Homa neighborhood in
southeastern Jerusalem and the order to close four Palestinian
offices in eastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials said that Israel should have made the
decision on further troop redeployments through consultations with
the PNA, which hoped to gain up to 30 percent of West
Bank rather than the 9 percent. Levy insisted that Israel
retain sole right of deciding the scope of further pullbacks.
</P>
<P>
Late today, Arafat will convene a meeting of PLO's Fatah
Central Committee to formulate the next response to Israel's
latest moves which he condemned as "conspiracies and tricks"
that threaten the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
