<HEADLINE> U.N. Peace-keepers in Angola Start Pulling Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Uruguayan peace
keepers started to pull out of Angola last weekend under a
decision by the U.N. Security Council at the end of 1996 on the
gradual withdrawal of all U.N. peace-keepers from the country.
</P>
<P>
All Uruguayan peace-keepers will withdraw before March 14 from
the southern African country, Lieutenant Puaa (one name), a
spokesman for Uruguayan peace-keepers said in central city Huambo
today.
</P>
<P>
Namibian peace-keepers will start pulling out of the country on
March 24 and Portuguese logistics personnel will end their duty
of terms here after a month, said the official Angolan News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Uruguayan peace-keepers hope the lasting peace will come
to the land suffering from almost 20 years of civil war as soon
as possible, said Puaa.
</P>
<P>
More than 7,000 U.N. peace-keepers arrived in Angola in early
1995 soon after a peace accord was signed by Angola's warring
sides.
</P>
<P>
However, the final date when all U.N. peace-keepers leave the
country is not available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
