<HEADLINE> AL Official: Israel Tries to Create "No War No </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 10 (Xinhua) -- In the latest expression of the
Arab frustration over the stalled peace process, an Arab League
(AL) official today accused Israel of trying to create a state of
"no war no peace" in the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
"Israel is trying to create a no-peace-no-war situation, the
same status that existed between the 1967 and 1973 Middle East
wars," said Arab League Assistant Secretary General Said Kamal
Said.
</P>
<P>
However, he voiced doubt about the viability of such a
state. "The current no-peace-on-war situation will be
short-lived, as it did not last in the post 1973 period," he
added.
</P>
<P>
If the U.S. rejects the U.N. intervention to challenge Israeli
settlement activity, she is required, in turn, as the sponsor of
peace, to play a positive role and rescue the peace process, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The international community has come to the conviction that
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu is looking for pretexts
to terminate the peace process and "equate the oppressed with the
oppressor," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arab outrage has been mounting over the recent Israeli
decisions to build new Jewish homes and close four Palestinian
offices in East Arab Jerusalem, as well as pull back from only 9
percent of the rural West Bank, instead of 30 percent as the
Palestinians had expected.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. veto of a European-sponsored U.N. Security Council
draft resolution against the Israeli settlement plan dealt
another blow to the Palestinians who are getting increasingly
frustrated with the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. veto has virtually created "a feeling of injustice"
in the Arab world, as observed by Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, who is currently on a five-day "saving-pace" tour in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat is
reportedly so pessimistic about peace talks with Israel that he
is thinking of leaving the self-rule Gaza Strip and moving his
operations to Cairo. But Mubarak has advised him against the
idea, which is feared to arouse confusion among his people and
put Israeli-Palestinian relations out of control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
