<HEADLINE> WFP to Distribute Food Relief in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
will this year distribute 2.9 million tons of food worth 1.4 Billion
U.S. Dollars as relief and development supplies to 90 countries
including Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
WFP country Director Irene Lacy told reporters here today it
was estimated so far that Tanzania needs 10,000 tons of maize and
1,000 tons of pulses to feed about 200,000 people who have been
affected by famine.
</P>
<P>
She said the exact requirement would be known after the monitoring
team which was dispatched to the affected regions today to assess the
situation, submitted their report.
</P>
<P>
'However we have recommended for an immediate supply of 10,000 tons
of maize and 1,000 tons of pulses," she explained, adding that the
team will be due back on March 25.
</P>
<P>
The WFP official further said the food would be procured
within Tanzania and later distributed to the affected areas, the
operation which was expected to take place before the end of this
month. It would cost the program between four and five million
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the WFP official, the monitoring team will visit
Arusha, Kilimanjaro, Coast, Lindi, Morogoro, Dodoma, Singida, Tabora,
Shinyanga, Mwanza and Mara regions to estimate the number of affected
people and identify locations of the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she said worldwide, a total of 50 million people were
expected to benefit from this WFP's supplies.
</P>
<P>
She further said half of the targeted people would benefit through
development projects whereas relief supplies would cover 14 million
displaced people, seven million refugees including 400,000 Zaire and
Burundi refugees currently in the country and four million victims of
natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The director said the supplies would be made by her organization in
recognition of the importance of food to human life.
</P>
<P>
"If there is no food there will be no peace, no democracy and no
development," she stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
