<HEADLINE> President: Turkey Attaches Importance to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel said here today that Turkey attaches importance to its
relations with neighboring Iran.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the press office of the presidential
palace said that Demirel expressed his anxiety over the recent
diplomatic crisis between Turkey and Iran during his meeting
with visiting Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati.
</P>
<P>
Velayati arrived here this morning for conveying to Demirel
an invitation from Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani to attend
a summit meeting of the Organization of the Islamic Conference
(OIC) scheduled in December in Tehran, capital of Iran.
</P>
<P>
Demirel stressed that the ties between Turkey and Iran should
go on in the way of respect to the principles of mutual
interests, friendship, good neighborhood and not interference
with other's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Before his meeting with Velayati, Turkish Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan said that Turkey attaches importance to the
Turkish-Iranian relations, the prosperity of the people and the
peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan said that the ties between the two countries had gone
forward in the past one year and Turkey and Iran are friendly
countries.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Velayati said that Iran and Turkey "had put
some difficulties under control with clever attitude and
patience in the past few days."
</P>
<P>
Following his meeting with his Turkish counterpart Tansu
Ciller, Velayati said that they held a "constructive and
productive talk" for the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that it is necessary to make more
cooperation not only in the bilateral relations, but also in the
international and regional issues between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Velayati had brought with him a message
from Rafsanjani concerning the current diplomatic dispute
between the two countries, which resulted in exchange of
expulsions of diplomats by both sides.
</P>
<P>
The dispute was triggered by Iranian Ambassador to Ankara
Muhammed Reza Baqeri who made a pro-Sharia (Islamic law) speech at
the commemoration of anti-Israeli "Al-quds (Jerusalem) Night"
gathering in the Turkish city of Sincan, 40 kilometers west of
Ankara last month.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Demirel sent Turkish Foreign Ministry
Undersecretary Ali Tuygan as special envoy to Iran and handed
over a written message to Rafsanjani in a bid to improve the
strained ties. 
</P>
