<HEADLINE> Canada Helps Tanzania Drill Wells in Dar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The government of Canada
has authorized an emergency contribution of 40.8 million Tanzania
Shillings (about 68,000 US Dollars) for the provision of wells to
key medical institutions in three districts of Dar es Sallam.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued here today by Canadian High Commission
said Canadian High Commissioner to Tanzania Verona Edelstein has
authorized the money as an immediate response for the water
scarcity in the Ilala, Kinondoni and Temeke districts of Dar es
Salaam.
</P>
<P>
The press release said the Canadian move was due to the Prime
Minister's efforts to mobilize resources in curbing the city
water crisis.
</P>
<P>
"In dealing with the critical water situation of Dar es
Salaam, this contribution will be made to the Tanzania Red Cross
Society (TRCS) and will be funded by the Canadian International
Development Agency (CIDA)," it added.
</P>
<P>
The TRCS will undertake a program of drilling one bore-hole at
each of the district hospitals while 40 shallow wells will be
installed in the three districts of the city.
</P>
<P>
Since last month, when the water level fell at River Ruve
following a prolonged dry spell in the country, some parts in the
city have been experiencing water scarcity, and out of them,
Ilala, Kinondoni and Temeke are most hit districts. 
</P>
