<HEADLINE> British Foreign Secretary on NATO Enlargement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Malcolm
Rifkind said here today that the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) is still the bedrock to European security and
stability.
</P>
<P>
Writing in an article to the Times newspaper today, Rifkind
said that NATO, which formed the bedrock of European security for
five decades, "is still our insurance policy against any serious
threat to peace in Europe."
</P>
<P>
Rifkind noted that enlarging NATO will be significant not only
to those Central European countries but to NATO member states as
well.
</P>
<P>
"By adding to the stability of Central Europe, we reduce the
risk of our sons and daughters ever having to fight in another
European war," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The prospect of joining NATO is helping Central European
countries to overcome ethnic and territorial disputes. And once
these countries feel secure, they will have the confidence to
develop better relations with Russia."
</P>
<P>
On Russo-NATO relations, the British foreign secretary said
that no European country is more important to European security
than Russia, whose size and importance demand that it should be
treated as a full partner.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that neither the new NATO nor the its
enlargement poses a threat to Russia, as "the alliance has no
plans, no intention, no reason to deploy nuclear weapons on the
territory of new members."
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that a deal will be struck this summer between
NATO and Russia to create a new strategic partnership," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
