<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Pharmacy Drug Sales Up 7 Pct in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Pharmacy drug sales in the world's
top 10 markets grew 7 percent to 143.8 billion US dollars in 1996,
according to data published today by IMS International, the
specialist pharmaceuticals industry market researchers.
</P>
<P>
On the US market, the world's biggest one and also one of the
fastest growing, drug sales rose 10 percent to 60.2 billion
dollars. Only Italy grew faster, rising 11 percent to 9 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Although Britain grew at the same rate as the US, its market
was much smaller as sales only stood at 11.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Germany remained Europe's biggest market, with sales
up 5 percent to 16.5 billion dollars. Drug sales in France rose 2
percent to 15.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, the world's second largest market, drug sales grew at
a relatively slow pace of 3 percent to 23.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The IMS International said that the star performers last year
were anti-depressants and blood agents, with the former recording
a 14 percent annual increase in sales to 20.3 billion dollars
and the latter rising 16 percent to 7.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Heart drug sales last year rose 3 percent to 25.5 billion
dollars, just ahead of digestive system drugs, where sales climbed
9 percent to 24.6 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
