<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon FM Describes European Peace Formula As </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz today described the European-sponsored peace formula based
on the principle of "total withdrawal for total security" as
"preliminary."
</P>
<P>
Boueiz made the remarks after a meeting with European Union
(EU) Middle East peace envoy Miguel Angel Moratinos this
afternoon, who delivered the formula to Lebanon today.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese foreign minister said that it is acceptable on
the condition that the formula meets the Arab position generally
and the Lebanese and Syrian position particularly, which demands
a complete Israeli withdrawal from all the occupied Arab lands.
</P>
<P>
"Because of this the first part of the expression really
constitutes the Lebanese and Syrian demand," the foreign
minister pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"For the second part," he said, "if it means the security to
which the Arab states should commit themselves, rather than
rights Israel will have on the lands it will withdraw and
conditions to limit the sovereignty of those Arab states, it
becomes acceptable. "
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on difference between the new formula
and the"land-for-peace" principle, Boueiz said, "what Moratinos
is suggesting is actually a preliminary formula through which he
is trying to activate the peace negotiations."
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process was inaugurated on the principle
of exchanging land for peace which was defined in the Madrid
conference in October, 1991.
</P>
<P>
"The land-for-peace principle includes the term of peace
which entails a determination of future political and other
relations, while the new formula deals only with the security,
which is easier to be achieved than the peace," the foreign
minister noted.
</P>
<P>
"For this reason the formula could be a bridge if it is
clearly crystallized and if Moratinos successfully persuades the
parties in the peace process to accept it," Boueiz added.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos arrived here from Damascus, the capital of Syria,
this morning to continue his peace mission in the region. He
held a meeting with the Lebanese foreign minister in the
latter's office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Urges Clinton to Use Influence on Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak today said the United States as a "full partner" in the
Middle East peace process should use its influence to pressure
Israel to reverse its decision to build a Jewish neighbor in Arab
east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
At a photo session before his discussions with President Bill
Clinton at the White House, Mubarak told reporters, "The president
is a full partner in the peace process. Without the United States,
it would be very difficult to continue the peace process. So it's
very important to have his influence."
</P>
<P>
Asked about a U.S. veto last Friday against a U.N. Security
Council resolution to call on Israel to abandon its housing
project in east Jerusalem, Clinton said he will answer the
question later this afternoon after his talks with Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said Sunday that it was unfortunate that the United
States vetoed the U.N. resolution, which would only encourage
Israel to push on with its housing construction in east Jerusalem
leading to a possible flare-up of violence in the region.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. move in the United Nations could lose its credibility
in the Arab world, and the Arabs would feel injustice played on
the U.S. side in handling issues like Jewish settlements in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He said he would ask Clinton to use his influence to stop the
Israeli government from carrying on with the construction plan.
</P>
<P>
The Arab world was angered over the U.S. veto and a Saudi-owned
newspaper urged Arab countries Sunday to boycott American products
including weapons.
</P>
<P>
The boycott would force the United States to "suffer from the
same means it uses against Iraq, Iran, Cuba and any country that
opposes its policy," the newspapers Al-Hayat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
