<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WEF Quickens Pace to Deploy Videocommunication Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The World Economic Forum (WEF) has
decided to quicken the implementation of its World Electronic
Community (WELCOM) inaugurated in early February, according to a
press release by the WEF here today.
</P>
<P>
Because of growing demands from the participants since the WEF
annual meeting in Davos, WELCOM will be implemented at a fast pace
and reach more than 1,000 global decision-makers by the end of the
year, the WEF said in its release.
</P>
<P>
An agreement has been made between the United Nations and the
WEF to equip the secretary-general and the heads of the UN
agencies with WELCOM in order for the UN to have better and faster
coordination and more efficient management.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the virtual community to be established among
WEF members and constituents, specific applications of WELCOM are
under discussion with organizations like the World Bank and the
international financial community to create a special hotline to
deal with possible global financial crises.
</P>
<P>
The new system is said to enable WEF members and constituents
to open up new business opportunities, facilitate expanded
commerce, joint ventures and strategic alliances, and enhance
global business and government understanding.
</P>
<P>
Some of the services WELCOM offers are multi-point
video-conferencing both with WELCOM and non-WELCOM members, a
24-hour multilingual concierge service, crisis management support,
direct face-to-face counseling with world experts and
organizations such as the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
