<HEADLINE> Lebanon Blasts US Veto of UN Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon today sharply criticized
the U.S. veto of a draft resolution by the U.N. Security Council
demanding Israel to abandon a recent housing plan in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held in his office, Lebanese Foreign
Minister Farez Boueiz said that the U.S. veto not only
"violated principles of the Middle East peace process," but also
"preempted the Security Council and paralyzed its role."
</P>
<P>
After a two-day debate, in which some 50 countries criticized
Israel's housing plans in East Jerusalem, Washington vetoed the
Security Council draft resolution, which denounced the plans as
"illegal and an obstacle to peace."
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese foreign minister pointed out that the veto also
violated the original policy of the U.S., which had announced
that it did not support or encourage Israel's settlement policy.
</P>
<P>
"What is more dangerous is in the veto's form, since the
U.S. automatically uses its right of veto whenever Israel and
its interests are involved," the Lebanese official said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. veto prompted an angry reaction from Arab
countries which called for an emergency session of the U.N.
General Assembly to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
Drafted by the European Union, the resolution enjoyed the
support of the U.N. Security Council's other 14 members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
