<HEADLINE> Eastern Africa Pledges Closer Coop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Presidents of Kenya, Tanzania
and Uganda have pledged continued supports for closer regional
cooperation among the three eastern African countries.
</P>
<P>
Their pledges were made in their messages published today in
commemoration of the forthcoming March 14 first anniversary of
the establishment of the Secretariat of the East African
Cooperation (EAC).
</P>
<P>
In his message, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi, the current
chairman of the EAC Authority, pledged "unqualified support" to
the forging of closer social and economic ties among the three
countries.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa sent a message to the EAC
Secretariat which was set up on March 14 last year, saying that
"much has been done in this first year to create a firm
foundation on which to continue building our cooperation."
</P>
<P>
He noted that "the political will to stay the course in our
three capitals remains firm and unshaken."
</P>
<P>
During the past year, he said, agreements have been translated
into greater practical cooperation in eastern Africa, leading to
a "faster and balanced social and economic progress".
</P>
<P>
In his statement on the eve of the first anniversary of the
EAC Secretariat, Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni said that
notable achievements have been made in the past year in building
a foundation for the re-integration of eastern Africa.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the regional cooperation would lead to
production on a larger scale, create more competition, improve
efficiency and result in better products.
</P>
<P>
The three presidents urged the Secretariat to work tirelessly
toward the speedy realization of the objectives of the East
African Cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
