<HEADLINE> Ethiopia's Somalis Urged to Help Drought Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Somalis living in the
south-eastern Somali region in Ethiopia today were urged to
assist the nationwide efforts in helping drought victims.
</P>
<P>
A report from Jijiga, the capital of the Somali region in
Ethiopia, said head of the Somali region Id Tahir Farah called on
residents and civil servants in the region to supply vehicles and
water vessels with them to contain the aggravating water
shortage.
</P>
<P>
Somalis should save life by contributing their share until
external relief aid reaches the concerned area, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Somali regional administration declared a state of
emergency on March 6 as some areas of the Somali region have seen
no rains since last September.
</P>
<P>
About 600,000 people there are facing acute shortage of
drinking water, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian government has dispatched a medical team to the
drought-hit area to control the spread of diseases affecting both
human beings and animals and caused by scarcity of water.
</P>
<P>
Tankers carrying with water sent by the central government
have also arrived at the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
