<HEADLINE> Fighting Going On in Kaya Town in Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese government spokesman,
Brigadier Tayeb Al Tayeb Ibrahim Mohamed Kheir, said today that
fighting was still going on in the town of Kaya adjacent to the
Ugandan borders.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, who is the Minister of Culture and Information,
said that the attack on the Kaya area was initiated from within
Ugandan territory targeting Sudanese border towns and villages
which are few hundred meters from the Ugandan borders.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that the offensive was mounted by large
numbers of tanks and heavy artillery which the Sudanese rebels did
not possess.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese Minister described the attack as "practical
manifestation of the aggressive designs as pronounced by Uganda
President Museveni when he openly disclosed a few days ago that
his problem with the Sudan would be settled in the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
The General Command of the Sudanese Armed Forces issued a
statement Sunday accusing Uganda of launching attacks on
Kaya, shelled the "Bazi" town and opened a route to the rebel
forces to proceed towards "Yei" area" of Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese national democratic alliance which groups northern
Sudanese opposition and southern Sudanese rebels launched a large
scale offensive in eastern Sudan on January 12, occupying the
towns of Kurmuk and Qissan close to the borders with Ethiopia. The
Sudanese government had then accused Ethiopia and Eritrea of
committing aggression against eastern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, press reports today said that the Sudan has
officially called upon the League of Arab States Sunday to
table the issue of "Ethiopian and Eritrean aggressions against
eastern Sudan" on the agenda of the upcoming Arab League
ministerial council meeting scheduled to take place on March 30 in
Cairo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
