<HEADLINE> Clinton Defends U.S. Veto of U.N. Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Monday defended his representative to the United Nations for
vetoing a Security Council's resolution calling on Israel to
abandon its decision to build Jewish homes in Arab east Jerusalem,
saying the United States went against the move because it was
"ill-advised".
</P>
<P>
"We felt that the resolution of the Security Council was...
ill-advised for the general reason that we generally prefer that
the Security Council resolutions not be injected into the peace
negotiations, first; and second, because there was specific
language in this resolution that we have previously vetoed because
we also feel it attempts to shape the final status negotiations,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a joint news conference at the White
House after his talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton admitted that Israel's decision to build a Jewish
neighbor in Arab east Jerusalem "would not build confidence, would
not be conducive to negotiations; would be seen by the
Palestinians and others as an attempt to, in effect, precondition
some of the final status issues."
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, however, said: "Such developments (by Israel's housing
plan) make the peace process a fragile and vulnerable one.
</P>
</TEXT>
