<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Tries to Exempt From European Summer Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 11 (Xinhua) -- France is facing an uphill
struggle this week to exempt itself from European summer time,
since all of its 14 European Union partners have indicated that
they will support a continuation of the one-hour clock change.
</P>
<P>
As EU government officials met in Paris today to set a strategy
for the recent meeting of EU transportation ministers in Brussels,
French officials conceded that their struggle against summer time,
which France helped to institute in the mid-1970s as an
energy-saving measure, had failed.
</P>
<P>
However, French officials said that Secretary of State
Anne-Marie Idrac would demand an exemption for France from
European summer time, which would leave Paris a one-hour time
difference from other European Continental capitals in the summer.
</P>
<P>
French officials said that another alternative which Idrac
would demand would be a shorter prolongation of summer time when
EU ministers consider legislation to extend the current time
system from 1998 to 2001.
</P>
<P>
EU officials expressed certain willingness to consider the
latter option, but they dismissed the prospect for France's
exemption as a practical nightmare.
</P>
<P>
Both The Netherlands, the current EU president, and Germany,
France's biggest neighbor, argue that a time change at the French
border would cause Europe's train and plane schedules in total
havoc.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations will not affect the switch of summer time this
year. European countries are going to set their clocks ahead by
one hour at 2 A.M. on March 30, a Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Industry Grows 10.4 Percent In First Two Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The first two months of 1997 saw
the added value of China's industry rise at an annual rate of 10.4
percent in real terms to 278.7 billion yuan, the State Statistics
Bureau announced today.
</P>
<P>
According to a bureau report, the added value of state-owned
enterprises was 168.7 billion yuan, an annual increase of 6.3
percent. The state-owned firms alone turned out 143.8 billion
yuan-worth of added value, 4.6 percent more than in the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The light industry grew slightly faster than the heavy industry
during that period, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
The light industry generated an added value of 114.9 billion
yuan, up 10.9 percent, while the added value of the heavy industry
rose 10 percent to 163.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In the light industrial sector, production of most durable goods
witnessed relatively quick growth.
</P>
<P>
Production of washing machines, refrigerators, air conditioners
and cameras rose in a range from between 11 to 21.8 percent.
Production of textile products either decreased or edged up.
</P>
<P>
In the heavy industrial sector, energy and major raw materials
continued to enjoy stable growth in January and February.
</P>
<P>
Production of the country's primary energy stood at 181 million
tons of coal, a rise of 4.2 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The report said that because southern China has entered the
spring plowing season and the north is now preparing for it,
strong demand for fertilizers and pesticide has pushed up their
production.
</P>
<P>
China produced 4.65 million tons of fertilizers during the
first two months, an increase of 12.3 percent, and 80,000 tons of
chemical pesticides, up 2.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
