<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Seizes 175 Tons of Narcotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced here today that
its armed police have seized 175 tons of narcotics in the past
11 months of the current Iranian calendar year ending March 20,
1997.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Ali Mohammad Besharati said that the Law
Enforcement Forces arrested 12,000 drug traffickers, including
3,200 foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani called for "any
effort to fight drug trafficking and addiction," the official
news agency IRNA said today.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani said infiltration of Mafia groups into the power
centers of the world and their attempts to spread corruption have
deteriorated the problem of drug trafficking and addiction
across the globe.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani criticized the cultural policy of the West and the
double standard of the big powers in dealing with the drug
producing countries.
</P>
<P>
The support of the "arrogant powers" for the governments
involved in cultivation and trade of illicit drugs such as
Afghanistan proved that the big powers are not sincere in their
campaign against drug trafficking, Rafsanjani noted.
</P>
<P>
He termed the U.S. publicity over its allocation of 16
billion U.S. dollars to fighting drug-related crimes and
allotment of another 400 billion dollars for this purpose next
year as a mere gesture.
</P>
<P>
The president recommended that cultural means including
satellite TV networks should be used to identify and remove the
cultural roots of drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
Iran is a transit route for drugs coming from Pakistan and
Afghanistan destined for Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
