<HEADLINE> Cooperation Boosted between China, Bell Labs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- In a move to forge a closer tie
with US-based Bell Laboratories, China's State Education
Commission (SEC) signed a memo of understanding with Bell here
today to jointly launch research centers in Chinese universities.
</P>
<P>
Wei Yu, vice minister of SEC, said at the signing ceremony that
the MOU signals a good start for the cooperation between China's
education community and the prestigious scientific institutes of
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Bell Labs, which holds an advantageous position in the world in
the research of electronics, computers and telecommunications,
will expand its involvement in China's universities by setting up
laboratories together with the SEC and entering into other
cooperation projects here, said Carl Hsu, vice president of Bell
Labs.
</P>
<P>
The cradle of scores of historical technical breakthroughs such
as the laser, transistor, telecom satellite, digital
program-controlled switching machine and cellular phone, Bell Labs
is now a research arm of Lucent Technologies Co., the largest
supplier of telecom equipment in the world.
</P>
<P>
Bell boasts 26,000 patents and seven Nobel laureates.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the signing ceremony were Randy Yeh, chairman of
Lucent Technologies (China) Co., and presidents of China's three
most prestigious universities,i.e., Beijing University, Qinghua
University and Jiaotong University. 
</P>
</TEXT>
