<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Director-General Opposes Human Cloning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- World Health Organization (WHO)
Director-General Hiroshi Nakajima today expressed his opposition
to possible human cloning following Scottish scientists' recent
successful cloning of an adult sheep.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released today in Geneva, Nakajima called for a
public debate at national and international level to establish
regulations on the issue.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged the significance of the medical achievement,
saying that it may yield benefits including therapeutic
applications.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the use of cloning for the replication of
human individuals was not acceptable as it would violate some of
the basic principles governing medically assisted procreation.
</P>
<P>
Nakajima recalled the opinion of a scientific group organized
by the Special Program of Research Development and Research
Training in Human Reproduction (HRP) to review the technical
aspects of medically assisted procreation and related ethical
issues.
</P>
<P>
The group underlined the need to "respect the freedom
indispensable for scientific research and creative activity," but
also stressed that extreme forms of experimentation including
human cloning must be prohibited.
</P>
<P>
Nakajima stressed that technical and ethical guidelines must be
observed to ensure that health and dignity of human being are
fully protected.
</P>
<P>
He said a public debate at both national and international
level would discuss the matter of cloning and set up certain
regulations based on these guidelines.
</P>
<P>
WHO will take the lead in organizing the debate. The HRP's next
meeting on April 23-25 will review the issue of cloning to prepare
for the debate, Nakajima said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illicit Fees for Rural Education Banned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Central government departments
have issued a circular nationwide aimed at prohibiting the
collection of illicit fees for rural education and easing the
financial burden of farmers.
</P>
<P>
In some areas, education fees are excessive and some are
diverted for other purposes -- practices which must be halted
and banned, according to the circular, which was issued by the
State Education Commission, the State Planning Commission, and the
ministries of Agriculture and Finance.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the circular, the four departments have also
formulated regulations to supervise fund raising for rural
education.
</P>
<P>
The regulations state that the fees should be charged in
accordance with the development of the local economy and education
as well as the farmers' financial status.
</P>
<P>
Money collected from farmers should only be used to build new
buildings and renovate rundown buildings for the state-run
primary and middle schools, instead of being redirected as bonuses
or welfare benefits for teachers, or as a substitute for state
education funds, according to the regulations.
</P>
<P>
With county government approval, township governments will
collect the education fees for those schools which have
deteriorating facilities or need new classrooms.
</P>
<P>
Farmers can pay the rural education fees through various means,
including direct cash payments, or by providing goods or
labor.
</P>
<P>
No education fees should be collected from farmers in poor or
disaster-stricken areas, where state education funding can make
ends meet for local schools, according to the regulations.
</P>
<P>
Any violation of the regulations should be corrected within the
period set by the local governments, and violators should be
punished or even taken to court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
