<HEADLINE> Swearing-in Ceremony for Nepal's New PM Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The swearing-in ceremony for
Nepal's newly appointed Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand was
postponed to Wednesday as coalition partners are still in the
process of working out the formation of the cabinet, sources here
said today.
</P>
<P>
Chand, parliamentary leader of the National Democratic Party
(RPP), was appointed prime minister by King Birendra Monday after
he submitted a petition to form a new coalition government to be
joined by the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist,
CPN-UML) and the Nepal Goodwill Party (NSP).
</P>
<P>
He was earlier expected to announce his cabinet today after
taking oath of office.
</P>
<P>
However, as talks over the cabinet formation are still going on
between Chand and the biggest ruling partner CPN-UML, Chand had to
postpone his swearing-in ceremony, a source close to Chand's RPP
party said.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the CPN-UML, with its 90 MPs in the
205-seat lower house, is demanding a considerable number of
important portfolios in the cabinet or the council of ministers.
</P>
<P>
Chand's cabinet, expected to be announced Wednesday morning,
will include seven to 10 members from the three coalition
partners, namely the RPP, the CPN-UML and the NSP, according to
the source.
</P>
<P>
The compact cabinet will be expanded to a nearly 30-member one
after the government secures a confidence vote in parliament
within one month of its formation, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
