<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coal Miners Continue Blocking Bonn Government District </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Western German coal miners continued
their blockade of the government district here today after
negotiations between the government and trade union representatives
on mining subsidy cuts were postponed to Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The protest began early on Monday with miners surrounding the
headquarters of major political parties and causing traffic chaos
in Bonn. The authorities have said they will allow the protests to
continue.
</P>
<P>
Up to 20,000 miners were expected to join the Bonn
demonstration in protest against government plans to reduce annual
federal subsidies for western Germany's bituminous coal mines from
10 billion marks (about 5.8 billion U.S. dollars) currently to 5.5
billion marks (abut 3.2 billion dollars) by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the unprofitable deep-pit coal mines in the west of
Germany received a record handout of 11.2 billion marks (about 6.6
billion dollars) from the government and the state, it is reported.
</P>
<P>
Trade unions believe that the quick pace of subsidy reduction
by the government will result in mass unemployment in the coal
mining regions of the Ruhr Valley and Saarland, pushing up
unemployment in the country, which hit a record of 4.67 million,
or 12.2 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
Under the government plan, only about 35,000 jobs in mines out
of the current 85,000 should remain by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Trade unions demand the annual subsidies remain 6.5 billion
marks (about 3.8 billion dollars) by 2005 and express their
willingness to reduce the coal mining workforce to 45,000.
</P>
<P>
The mining trade union IG Bergbau leader, Hans Berger, was due
to hold talks with the government today, but the talks were
postponed to Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
