<HEADLINE> France Wants Exemption From European Summer Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 11 (Xinhua) -- France is facing an uphill
struggle this week to exempt itself from European summer time,
with all 14 of its European Union partners having indicated that
they will support a continuation of the one-hour clock change.
</P>
<P>
As government officials met in Paris to set their strategy for a
meeting of EU transportation ministers here Tuesday, French
officials conceded that their campaign against summer time, which
France helped institute in the mid-1970s as an energy-saving
measure, had won no converts.
</P>
<P>
However, they said that Secretary of State Anne-Marie Idrac would
demand an exemption for France, which would leave Paris with
a one-hour time difference from other Continental capitals in the
summer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
