<HEADLINE> Cambodian King Seeks Advice on Case Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian King Norodom
Sihanouk today sought advice from a top judicial official on his
intervention in the case of Srun Vong Vannak, security chief of
the Khmer Nation Party (KNP), a KNP press release said.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to Minister of Justice Chem Snguon, King Sihanouk
wrote: "I have received a letter from H.E. Sam Rainsy dated March
10, 1997 requesting me to intervene in order to ensure that the
public authorities respect the Constitution, the laws of the
Kingdom and human rights in the case of Mr. Srun Vong Vannak."
</P>
<P>
"I am enclosing the above-mentioned letter and asking Your
Excellency to advise me on what I should do," the King wrote in
the letter sent from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
KNP President Sam Rainsy wrote to King Sihanouk Monday to ask
for a royal order to force municipal authorities to allow KNP
security chief Srun Vong Vannak access to legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
Vannak, also a member of the party's steering committee, was
arrested on February 14 on charge of masterminding the murder of
Kov Samuth, a brother-in-law of Second Prime Minister Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
Vannak's arrest came after a man identified as Suos Kasem
turned in himself to the police and confessed that he killed Kov
Samuth on November 19 on the order of Vannak, who offered him a
50,000 U.S. dollar reward for the act.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Phnom Penh Municipal Penal Police Mok Chito told
reporters last week that Suos Kasem, Vannak and another suspect in
the murder have confessed to the crime.
</P>
<P>
Rainsy said the charge against Vannak and the allegation by the
police are groundless and that the criminal procedure has violated
every point of the due process of law.
</P>
<P>
The KNP confirmed today it will stage a public demonstration on
March 12 to demand Vannak's release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
