<HEADLINE> Ukraine Seeks More Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors will soon be
allowed to buy stakes of up to 74 percent of Ukraine's most
promising industrial enterprises, said Industry Minister Valery
Mazur today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's enterprises in metallurgical, chemical,
woodworking and light industries have already teamed up with
foreign investors in more than 100 highly profitable joint
ventures, Mazur told a press conference today.
</P>
<P>
But "the amount of foreign investment is still too small," said
Mazur, who did not provide the total amount of foreign investment
in enterprises under his ministry.
</P>
<P>
"The largest investment -- 30 million U.S. dollars -- belongs
to the Spanish firm Transplan, but some of our enterprises are
worthy of investments ten times that size," he said.
</P>
<P>
Topping the ministry's list are a 350-million-dollar project to
produce ethylene and polyethylene at the Severodonetsky Azot
complex and a 160-million-dollar polypropylene processing plant in
Kalusha.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine also hopes to attract investors to mining enterprises
that sit on deposits of iron ore and other minerals.
</P>
<P>
"These mines are now being privatized, and they can yield
profit within three years of investment," said Mazur.
</P>
<P>
However, many foreign investors complain that corruption and
administrative decrees have jeopardized their ventures in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
"We're hesitant at this point, we need a more secure business
environment in 1997," said John Shmorhun, manager of Du Pont De
Nemours International S.A., a company active in the agro-chemical
industry.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Mazur promised that foreign investors
will get support form Prime Minister Pavel Lazarenki and President
Leonid Kuchma.
</P>
<P>
"If certain Ukrainian laws get in the way of a prominent
investor, they can be overridden by a government resolution or
even a presidential decree," added the minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
