<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Calls for Ceasefire in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 11 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today appealed to the international community to help force a
ceasefire in Zaire and to take emergency humanitarian action to
help refugees stranded in the civil war in the central African
country.
</P>
<P>
French government spokesman Alain Lamassoure said that Chirac
told a cabinet meeting "the humanitarian situation in Zaire is
tragic."
</P>
<P>
"No one can ignore it any longer. No one can remain
indifferent. We have to ask if there is not a sort of conspiracy
of silence," he quoted Chirac as saying.
</P>
<P>
Chirac reaffirmed France's support to the UN peace proposal
calling for an immediate end to hostilities in and withdrawal of
foreign forces from Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan-backed rebels fighting the government of French-backed
President Mobutu Sese Seko have captured a swathe of eastern
Zaire, driving Rwandan Hutu refugees before them, and threatened
the key garrison city of Kisangani on the Zaire river.
</P>
<P>
The french state secretary for emergency humanitarian action,
Xavier Emmanuelli, just back from his Africa tour, said in a
report to the meeting that some 400,000 Rwandan Hutu refugees are
believed to be holed out and in very poor condition.
</P>
<P>
Emmanuelli said that he was shocked by the lack of any
humanitarian organizations in eastern Zaire, where tens of
thousands of refugees fled Goma and Bukavu and 3,500 other
refugees are suffering from extreme weakness after four months of
wanderings.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that France launch its own mini-airlift while
awaiting wider international support.
</P>
<P>
Chirac proposed the Emmanuelli report be sent to the United
Nations, the European Union, and the United Nations Security
Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
