<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electricity To Be Rationed In Dar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Power rationing may start
any time in Tanzania's capital Dar es Salaam as the government
can no longer afford to meet the costs of generating
hydroelectric power by gas turbines, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that a prolonged drought has again affected
the generation of electricity at the main hydropower station in
Kidatu in Morogoro Region, Western Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The dry spell in Coast and Morogoro regions was only a
secondary reason for the new power shortage situation, according
to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Gas turbine generation of electricity was likely to prove too
expensive for the country, a factor overlooked in putting up the
plant.
</P>
<P>
Treasury coffers can no longer pay the monthly cost of 3.33
million U.S. Dollars to run the gas turbines commissioned in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Load shedding started in the last quarter of 1992 as power
generation declined owing to a fall in the water level at Kidatu
and the reserve dam at Mtera further up the River Basin.
</P>
<P>
Dam levels at Mtera and Nuyumba ya Mungun on the Pangani
Valley have declined on account of lower than average rainfall
for the last three years.
</P>
<P>
The government sought to put up the expensive plant after the
shedding started in 1992, but may now have to do without the
costly substitute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Khamenei Criticizes Western Monopoly of World Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Supreme Leader Ali
Khamenei today criticized the monopoly of western giant oil
companies in today's world oil market, which he described as
"oppressive" and "completely" against the interests of producers.
</P>
<P>
"The world oil market is structured to serve the interests of
the western multi-national oil companies," the state-run Tehran
Radio quoted Khamenei as saying.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement while touring Iman Khomeini Petrochemical
Complex in Iran's southwestern province of Khuzestan.
</P>
<P>
The complex is believed to be the largest one in the Middle
East, which was destroyed by Iraqi bombardment during the
eight-year war between Iran and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, Khamenei did not specify any foreign countries or
foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian leader stressed that the oil producers should sell
oil on the basis of their own will, decision and interests.
</P>
<P>
He said that "it is my heartfelt wish that we reach the stage
in which we would be able to cut the oil export at any time,"
adding "It is only then we can say we are the real owner of our
oil."
</P>
<P>
Iran, the second largest oil exporter and the fourth largest
oil producer in the world, pumps out about 3.6 million barrels of
crude and exports about 2.5 million barrels per day in line with
quota of Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
Iran is expected to earn about 19 billion U.S. dollars from oil
export during the current Iranian calendar year which ends on
March 20, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
