<HEADLINE> Namibian Fishermen Warned Against Illegal Fishing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Namibian Fisheries and
Marine Resources Minister Hifipunye Pohamba has warned Namibian
fishermen against fishing illegally in other countries'
territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian Broadcasting Corporation said Pohamba expressed
his concern over allegations of illegal fishing by Namibian
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
Addressing fishermen at Walvis Bay at the weekend, Pohamba
said South Africa and France had lodged a complaint against
Namibian vessels fishing illegally in their territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
Pohamba said the government understood the difficult position
facing local fishermen but warned that this did not justify them
stealing other countries' stocks.
</P>
<P>
To this effect, the Namibian government would support any
legal action taken by South Africa or France to discourage
illegal fishing, said the Minister.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian fisheries sector has experienced very poor
seasons in the past two years due to abnormal oceanic conditions,
resulting in heavy quota cuts and losses for the industry.
</P>
<P>
In the past, Namibia imposed very heavy penalties and seized
the vessels of those caught fishing illegally inside its own 200
mile exclusive economic zone.  
</P>
</TEXT>
