<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho Foreign Minister
Kelebone Maope has accused South Africa of dragging its feet on
concluding the customs union agreement with the mountain kingdom,
said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on Monday in Maseru, capital of the
kingdom, Maope said: "There is general feeling in government
circles that South Africa is not moving fast enough in concluding
the agreement."
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the Lesotho government would make further
efforts to compel the South African government to speed up the
process, said the Minister.
</P>
<P>
Maope also accused South Africa of engaging in negotiations
with western countries which would impact on the envisaged
customs union agreement.
</P>
<P>
He was apparently referring to South Africa's current
negotiations with the European Union for a free trade agreement,
which reportedly caused serious concerns to the countries in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho, a small land-locked country in the southern African
region, is widely believed under heavy influence of its big
neighbor, South Africa, both economically and politically.
</P>
