<HEADLINE> EU Likely to Tighten Food Safety Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) might
introduce tougher food-safety regulations following a report that
many of its member countries are failing to detect cases of the
"mad cow" disease.
</P>
<P>
Gerry Kiely, agriculture spokesman for the European Commission,
said Monday that the executive agency is already considering ways
to improve Union-wide surveillance of the disease after the
internal report highlighted a number of shortcomings in the food
safety mechanism.
</P>
<P>
The report said existing EU food safety laws including controls
over meat plants have not been uniformly introduced or respected.
</P>
<P>
Kiely declined to elaborate on what measures the EU might take
to tighten food safety, but he left open the possibility of
reviving a proposal to ban the sales of beef for human or animal
consumption.
</P>
<P>
Such a ban was rejected by EU farm ministers last December.
</P>
