<HEADLINE> Conditions for Cross-Strait Talks Not Yet Ripe: Tang Shubei (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The conditions and political
atmosphere for resumption of talks between two organizations
across the Taiwan Straits are not yet ripe since the Taiwan
authorities have not returned to the "one China" principle, a
Chinese official who handles Taiwan affairs said today.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here today, Tang Shubei, executive
vice-chairman of the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan
Strait (ARATS), said the ARATS has always stood for talks under
the "one China" principle and proposed for a second "Wang-Koo
Meeting" in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Tang recalled that he visited Taiwan in May 1995 to make
arrangements with the Foundation for Exchange Across the Taiwan
Strait for the second "Wang-Koo Meeting," which stands for another
meeting between Wang Daohan, president of the Beijing-based ARATS
and Koo Chen-pu, president of the Taibei-based Strait Exchange
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
In June, however, Lee Teng-hui visited the United States, which
seriously poisoned the atmosphere across the straits. So the ARATS
had to announce the suspension of the second "Wang-Koo Meeting"
and other talks between the two organizations at different levels,
he said.
</P>
<P>
After three years of talks between ARATS and the strait
exchange foundation, he noted, ARATS became aware that the
fundamental differences between the two sides hinged on their
political difference which must be resolved through political
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Just as Premier Li Peng noted in his government report at the
ongoing NPC session that "the two sides of the Taiwan Straits will
settle disputes through political negotiations on the basis of
'one China' principle and gradually achieve the peaceful
reunification of the motherland."
</P>
<P>
"We can negotiate on some routine issues while the two sides of
the Taiwan Straits conduct political negotiations," Premier Li
said.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Tang also reiterated the Chinese
government's "one China" stance. He quoted President Jiang Zemin
as saying in an earlier important speech on the Taiwan issue that
there is only one China in the world and Taiwan is part of China,
and that China's sovereignty and territorial integrity cannot be
separated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conditions for Cross-Strait Talks Not Yet Ripe: Tang Shubei (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With regard to Taiwan's efforts to develop non-governmental
economic and cultural ties with other countries, Tang said that
"we do not hold differing views...but we are in opposition to its
activities of so-called 'expanding living space internationally',
which is aimed to go in for 'two Chinas' or 'one China, one
Taiwan'."
</P>
<P>
"Only after the peaceful reunification of the motherland is
accomplished can the Taiwan compatriots truly and fully share with
the Chinese people of all other ethnic groups the dignity and
honor attained by our great motherland," said Jiang Zemin in early
1995 in his speech on pushing forward the peaceful reunification
of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
On the "one China" principle, he said, the two organizations
reached vocal census at the end of 1992 which means the two sides
should adhere the "one China" principle. Owing to difference
between the two sides, we can leave the political implications of
"one China" principle for the future.
</P>
<P>
On investment by Taiwan businessmen, Tang said, the motherland
will protect the legitimate interests of Taiwan businessmen
according to the Law on the Protection of Investment of the Taiwan
Compatriots enacted by the National People's Congress in 1993 and
the 22 provisions formulated by the State Council to encourage
Taiwan investment. Special preferences will be given in line with
relevant regulations, he said.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation and the Taiwan Affairs Office of the State
Council and other related departments are studying the details on
the Law on the Protection of Investment of the Taiwan Compatriots.
The draft law will be worked out soon to solicit suggestions from
various walks of life.  
</P>
</TEXT>
