<HEADLINE> Sino-US Relations Rely on Principles, Not Bribery: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman said here today it is ridiculous to claim that the
development of Sino-US relations could be influenced by offers of
money,
</P>
<P>
At a news conference here today, Spokesman Cui Tiankai refuted
recent allegations by some US media organizations that China made
political donations to the U.S. Democratic Party, in an attempt to
bribe the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
He said that the healthy development of relations between China
and the United States relies on the faithful implementation of the
three joint communiques which set out the principles of the
bilateral relationship.
</P>
<P>
He said that China maintains a clear stance of non-interference
in internal affairs when forging ties with other countries.
</P>
<P>
China is not interested in using unjustifiable means to
interfere in other countries' internal affairs, nor will it
approve such activities by any other country, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that China is a developing country whose economic
construction and growth generate excessive demands for money. It
has no money to spare on election donations for a US political
party, and has no desire to spend money in this way, he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that in the past, the US media had reported
"intelligence information" about China's alleged activities, which
was ultimately proved groundless.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Sino-US relations should not be affected by
hearsay. Instead, the two sides should focus on common interests
and the overall need for cooperation and long-term development of
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
China wishes that the US congress and the US public will learn
more about the real situation in China, and is ready to
establish normal contacts with them, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that China welcomes members of the US congress,
including its leaders, to visit China.
</P>
<P>
"This will be conducive to the development of the relations
between the two countries," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
