<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Urged to be More Open in Economic Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN countries should apply
openness in their economic policies to make way for cooperation
among themselves to push for the early realization of the
grouping's single market, Indonesia's Chamber of Commerce and
Industry chairman said here today.
</P>
<P>
"As an economic bloc, the ASEAN has agreed not to close (its
doors) to others. Thus, efforts to forge cooperation among its
members do not mean that it would ignore non-ASEAN countries,"
Aburizal Bakrie said after opening the 53rd meeting of the ASEAN
Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
"We will even be more intensive in inviting non-ASEAN countries
to form cooperation with them or merely ask for their inputs," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Bakrie said the chamber will focus on three sectors -- the
capital goods sector, which continues to show a trade deficit; the
food and agriculture sector, which involves the ability to feed
the ASEAN region's 500 million people; and the tourism sector,
which is a main source of foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
Bakrie, who chairs the ASEAN chamber, said that to integrate
the ASEAN market into the global market, it needs special
management.
</P>
<P>
He said opportunities outside ASEAN must be found through
strategic alliances with other countries to enhance the region's
industrial strength.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN chamber should thus prepare "a map of journey" toward
the global market and one way is by organizing the first ASEAN
business summit, which opens Wednesday and will be attended by
some 600 businessmen, including those from non-ASEAN countries or
regions, he added.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN (the Association of Southeast Asian Nations) groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand
and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
