<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Draft Business Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Substantial expansion was seen in
1996 in China's bank draft sector, which involves the businesses
of remittance, discounting and re-discounting, according to the
People's Bank of China, the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Last year, along with the promulgation of the Law on Bills, the
draft businesses were given strong legal protection.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, bills of exchange worth a total of 389.8 billion yuan
were issued in the country, while commercial banks discounted
226.4 billion yuan and the People's Bank of China re-discounted
725.8 billion yuan, up 61.5 percent, 98.2 percent and 60.9 percent,
respectively, over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the development of the commercial draft sector
and its related businesses has stepped up the integration between
commercial credit and bank credit, broadened the channel for
enterprises to raise funds, improved the structure of credit
assets of commercial banks, and increased the means for the
central bank to exercise macro-economic control.
</P>
<P>
Currently, they point out, bank draft businesses and other
businesses concerned are concentrated in the eastern, coastal and
relatively developed areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that the development of bill businesses relies
on the existence of a mature commodity economy.
</P>
<P>
According to information from the central bank, in 1996, the
ratio between acceptance, discount and re-discount stood at 3:2:1.
</P>
<P>
The country's bill market will be further developed by properly
expanding the general volume of re-discounts and pushing forward
the expansion of the businesses of acceptance, discount and
re-discount. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
