<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Population Rose by 12.7 million in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- China's total population reached
1.22 billion in 1996, up 12.7 million over the figure of 1995,
according to the latest survey of the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
About 23.67 million people were born in the country last year,
and the natural growth rate was 1.04 percent, said the survey.
</P>
<P>
An average 21 million people are born in China each year -- an
annual increase of about 13 million, said Peng Peiyuan, state
councillor and minister in charge of the State Family Planning
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a national forum on family planning and
environmental protection, which was held in Beijing on Saturday,
Peng said that there is still an imbalance between family planning
work in various parts of the country, and that in the middle and
western parts of China, and that poor areas will face many
problems.
</P>
<P>
The population census of 1990 showed that the number of women
of child-bearing age in Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region, Jiangxi, Yunnan and Guizhou provinces,
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region and Tibet Autonomous Region will
reach its peak during the 1995-2000 period, she said.
</P>
<P>
This will make it difficult to lower the birth rate in those
areas, Peng said.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that a variety of new problems keep cropping
up, and the family planning situation of the floating population
continues to cause difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The State Family Planning Commission will list population
control and the work to improve people's lives in the general
program for poverty-relief, she said.
</P>
<P>
The "Happy Project" was launched by the Chinese Population
Welfare Foundation, the Family Planning Association of China and
China Population Newspaper in 1995 to help the poor mothers in
rural areas. It has collected more than 20 million yuan (about 2.4
million US dollars) and helped 17,000 poor families in 22
counties, Peng said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
