<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Produces Fewer Engineers: De Klerk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 11 (Xinhua) -- South Africa produces
dramatically fewer engineers than countries in the developed
world, with local tertiary institutions training only 32
engineers per million people compared with the 600 per million in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
The figures were revealed by the opposition National Party
leader De Klerk at the opening of an international construction
symposium, the Federation Internationale de la Precontrainte
Symposium, in Johannesburg on Monday.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk quoted statistics indicating that 393 engineers had
left South Africa in 1994, a 68.7 percent rise compared with that
of 1992.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has to analyse the reasons for the loss of too
many professional people and then take the necessary rectifying
steps to stop the brain exodus, said De Klerk.
</P>
<P>
He also highlighted productivity and labor relations as
matters of special importance if South Africa's international
competitiveness was to be improved.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk urged the African National Congress-led government,
organized labor and private sector to work together to strike a
deal to increase competitivity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
