<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Japanese Party Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
said here today he hopes that both China and Japan will view
Sino-Japanese relations from a "long-term and strategic
perspective," and handle bilateral ties in a way that benefits
both sides and safeguards peace in Asia and the world.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, also the general secretary of the Chinese Communist
Party (CPC) Central Committee, made the remarks at a meeting with
Doyi Takako, head of the Japanese Socialist Democratic Party, at
Zhongnanhai, headquarters of the central government.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Communist Party and the Chinese government have
always paid close attention to the Sino-Japanese relations and
have been devoted to the cause of maintaining and developing the
friendship between the two countries, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The leader said Takako and other members of delegation are "old
friends" who have contributed to the normalization of the
relations between the two countries and to promoting the sound
growth of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
"We will not forget what your Party has done to maintain
and develop the Sino-Japanese friendship," he told Japanese guests.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 25th anniversary of the normalization of
the relations between China and Japan, Jiang said, adding that
getting the bilateral relations to their present level has not
been easy.
</P>
<P>
"It is worth redoubling our efforts to treasure the
relationship that is the result of the efforts of several
generations," Jiang noted. "We sincerely hope that the Japanese
government will stick to the spirit of the Sino-Japanese Joint
Statement and the Sino-Japanese Treaty of Friendship and push
ahead, in a down-to-earth way, the healthy and stable development
of bilateral relations."
</P>
<P>
Takako thanked Jiang for meeting with her, and said the
contacts between her Party and the Chinese Communist Party had
enhanced mutual understanding and friendship.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Democratic Party heeds the friendly and
cooperative relations between the two countries, she said, adding
that maintaining and developing the ties is of great importance
not only to the two countries, but also to peace and development
in Asia and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the meeting were Li Shuzheng, minister of the
International Department of the CPC Central Committee, and
Japanese Ambassador to China Yoshiyasu Sato. 
</P>
</TEXT>
