<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electricity To Be Rationed In Dar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Power rationing may start
any time in Tanzania's capital Dar es Salaam as the government
can no longer afford to meet the costs of generating
hydroelectric power by gas turbines, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that a prolonged drought has again affected
the generation of electricity at the main hydropower station in
Kidatu in Morogoro Region, Western Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The dry spell in Coast and Morogoro regions was only a
secondary reason for the new power shortage situation, according
to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Gas turbine generation of electricity was likely to prove too
expensive for the country, a factor overlooked in putting up the
plant.
</P>
<P>
Treasury coffers can no longer pay the monthly cost of 3.33
million U.S. Dollars to run the gas turbines commissioned in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Load shedding started in the last quarter of 1992 as power
generation declined owing to a fall in the water level at Kidatu
and the reserve dam at Mtera further up the River Basin.
</P>
<P>
Dam levels at Mtera and Nuyumba ya Mungun on the Pangani
Valley have declined on account of lower than average rainfall
for the last three years.
</P>
<P>
The government sought to put up the expensive plant after the
shedding started in 1992, but may now have to do without the
costly substitute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
