<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's Sole Hydroelectric Power Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Power generation capacity at
Owen Falls Power station, uganda's sole hydroelectric station,
has been increased from 150 to 180 mw, reported local daily "the
New Vision" today.
</P>
<P>
This occurred following completion of its refurbishment
recently, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The upgrading, which costs Uganda Electricity Board about 30
million U.S. Dollars, will reduce power loadshedding in the
country by 50 percent starting next month, it said.
</P>
<P>
The fund to upgrade the station was granted to the government
by the British Overseas Development Association and the
refurbishing work started in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Power demand in Uganda is 220 mw, and the upgrading of the
Owen Falls Power Station will reduce the loadshed to 40 mw.
</P>
<P>
However, the power load was growing faster (2 percent every
month) than the board can cope with.
</P>
<P>
Before rehabilitation of the station started in 1989, there
was no loadshedding in the country for power shortage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Language Teachers Working Excessive Hours </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Ninety percent of Hong Kong
language teachers are under an enormous workload, spending seven
days a week, five hours a night marking students' compositions,
according to a survey published in today's South China Morning
Post.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted in January by the Professional Teachers'
Union, showed that Chinese and English language teachers have to
spend 35 hours a week after school, including weekends and
holidays, marking students' assignments.
</P>
<P>
The union's chairman, Cheung Man-kwong, stated that it was
"extremely inhuman" for teachers to work such long hours.
</P>
<P>
Among the 580 Chinese and English language teachers
interviewed, 50 percent said their workload was heavy and 40
percent said it was extremely heavy.
</P>
<P>
The survey sent 1,000 questionnaires to teachers at 200
secondary schools and 300 primary schools in the territory and
nearly 60 percent responded.
</P>
<P>
The union suggested that the Education Department increase the
number of language teachers and limit the number of classes they
teach from three to two.
</P>
<P>
The department should also encourage teachers to adopt more
flexible ways, such as using audio-visual material in their
teaching, the union said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
