<HEADLINE> More Leprosy Patients Registered in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 11 (Xinhua) -- India's Minister of State for
Health and Family Welfare Saleem Sherwani said here today that
there are 590,000 leprosy patients in the country, accounting for
52 percent of a total of 1.26 million leprosy cases in the world.
</P>
<P>
In reply to a question in the upper house of parliament, he
said that to meet this challenge all the 490 districts in the
country have been covered under the multi-drug therapy scheme.
</P>
<P>
A national leprosy eradication program is being implemented in
the country as a centrally-sponsored scheme to eliminate leprosy,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the blind, the minister said that there are about 12
million blind people in the country and of which 80 percent have
incurred blindness due to cataract which is curable by simple
surgery.
</P>
<P>
Cataract patients are treated free of charge through cataract
surgery performed in eye camps, organized by government and
non-governmental organizations, he added.  
</P>
