<HEADLINE> HK's Unit Trust Inflows Post Two-year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's unit trust industry
attracted net inflows of 168 million US dollars in January, the
largest amount ever recorded in a month since 1994, according to
local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
The figure could be largely attributed to the buoyant stock
exchange, said Peter Lord, vice-chairman of the Hong Kong
Investment Funds Association (HKIFA).
</P>
<P>
"The massive inflows mainly related to the rally in the Hong
Kong stock market, especially in the fourth quarter of 1996," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The HKIFA was very pleased with the strong net inflows,
especially after the net redemption recorded for three consecutive
months, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, the marked improvement of sales was
not across the board. Of the 14 sectors, half turned in net
inflows while the rest posted net outflows.
</P>
<P>
The leader in terms of net inflows was Hong Kong equity funds,
which pulled in 138 million US dollars, or 82 percent of the total
in January.
</P>
<P>
This is the third consecutive month that the sector ranked
first in net sales.
</P>
<P>
The HKIFA figures represent the retail and some institutional
sales of 45 fund management companies.  
</P>
