<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA,!March 11 (Xinhua) -- An estimated 26,000 Sudanese
refugees in transit camps in Koboko, northwestern Uganda, have
refused to move to Rhino camp about 40 miles southeast of Koboko,
reported the local daily "the New Vision" today.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations High Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) was
quoted as saying the refugees preferred to return to Sudan than
be transferred to Rhino camp, where over 30,000 other Sudanese
refugees are living.
</P>
<P>
The refugees were being transferred for security reasons
because Sudanese troops and Sudanese backed Uganda rebels often
target the refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
The local authorities resolved last week to start an emergency
transfer program of the refugees. However, the refugees refused
to board the lorries which were to take them to Rhino camp.
</P>
