<HEADLINE> One Million S. African Children Stunted in Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 11 (Xinhua) -- More than one million South
African children under the age of five nationwide suffer from
some form of stunted growth, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey released by the Medical Research Council
(MRC) on Monday in Cape Town, children's stunted growth was due
to a number of reasons including repeated diarrhoea episodes,
malnutrition, and iron and vitamin A deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
The MRC's nutritional intervention research programme would
also conduct a study to determine the possible effect of
micronutrients on the growth of children, said the source.
</P>
<P>
Researchers hoped to determine whether micronutrient
supplementation would have a positive effect on the growth and
mental development of infants.
</P>
<P>
The MRC further stressed evidence from previous studies had
shown that the period when babies were weaned onto solid foods
was also the period when stunting started in affected children.
</P>
