<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Redoubles Efforts To Combat Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 11 (Xinhua) -- China's biggest city of Shanghai
will see another district lifted out of heavy pollution before the
end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Taopu District, an industrial area focussed on chemical
production in the northwest of Shanghai, had serious pollution
problems at the end of last decade.
</P>
<P>
The district, covering an area of 15 square kilometers, has
over 50 enterprises. Over the past 30 years, a large quantity of
acid and alkali spewed out by the factories, along with other
harmful gases, has caused serious pollution problems in the region.
</P>
<P>
The city government has spent some one billion yuan (about 120
million US dollars) in the district's environmental protection
projects over the past decade, statistics say. As a result, nearly
a hundred polluting sources have been improved.
</P>
<P>
Before the end of this year, Shanghai will dismantle over 50
medium and small-sized boilers in the district. "This action is
expected to reduce 95 percent of the smoke and dust, and 45
percent of the sulphur dioxide spewed out," said an official with
the district government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a sewage treatment plant with a capacity to dispose
of 80,000 tons of waste water daily will be completed in
mid-1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
