<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harare Takes Measures to Reduce Water Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Harare city council will fine any
company guilty of polluting the city's water courses at least
5,000 U.S. Dollars plus 50 U.S. Dollars a day for the period that
the pollution continues.
</P>
<P>
The decision was part of efforts to reduce water pollution and
industrial effluent in the city and was made at a council meeting
recently, local daily "The Herald" reported today.
</P>
<P>
On prevention of pollution, councillors at the meeting agreed
to impose strict measures to ensure that all factories, old and
new, should have pre-treatment facilities to bring their effluent
to standards laid down by the urban councils act.
</P>
<P>
These pre-treatment facilities will be made a statutory
requirement before industrialists are allowed to operate.
</P>
<P>
The council needs about 1.26 million U.S. Dollars to achieve
internationally accepted water and waste water quality monitoring
systems.
</P>
<P>
The situation in water polluting in Harare has been
deteriorating in recent years. Fish have died at Lake Chivero and
Lake Manyame, Harare's main water reservoirs, with the cause
often linked to industrial waste discharged into the Manyame
River catchment area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
