<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Discovers Ancient Sculptural Masterpiece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 11 (Xinhua) -- A rare and unique antique has been
found in Egypt when a farmer dug foundation for his new house
recently, an Egyptian Gazette report said today.
</P>
<P>
The unidentified farmer hit upon a limestone statue, 95
centimeters high and 25 centimeters wide when he was laying the
foundation for his new house, about 300 meters off a temple in
Zagazig city, Sharkia, Eastern Arabian Desert.
</P>
<P>
The new find, that depicts a woman sitting on a chair in a
shape of a lion's leg, holding three small boys in her arms, is a
rare and priceless work of sculptural craft, said Ali Hassan,
secretary general of the Higher Council, an official body in
charge of protecting cultural relics in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
"The ancient statue has no equal in the long history of
Egypt's civilization and the world's art of sculpture," the
official was quoted by today's Egyptian Gazette as telling a press
conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
The statue probably dates back to the New Kingdom (1570
B.C.-332 B.C), Hassan said. No one knows exactly who this woman
is, but she certainly had a relationship with the kingdom,
because the statue contains precious stones, he added.
</P>
<P>
The three smaller statues standing in front of the woman's
chest have inlaid cornelian necklaces which are still in a good
condition but the heads of two of the three are missing. The
bigger statue also carries an incomplete statue of a girl on the
pillow on her leg.
</P>
<P>
Hassan said that surveys are being performed in the area where
the statue was discovered to find the missing part, then it will
be restored before being put on display after all the studies
have been conducted.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes the statue had been removed from its
original place. "In all probability this statue, which was found
on March 2, was stolen by someone who buried it beside the
farmer's house," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
