<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kissinger: Let Southeast Asian Countries Decide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Secretary of State
Henry Kissinger said here today that Southeast Asian nations
should be left to decide by themselves when they encounter
political and internal issues.
</P>
<P>
Kissinger made the remarks at the University of the
Philippines, where he was conferred a honorable Doctorate of Law
degree.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the conferment ceremony, Kissinger, who arrived
here Monday for a four-day visit, said that Southeast Asian
countries should be left to decide for themselves when they
encounter political and internal problems "as this part of the
world will play a major role in the world in the coming years."
</P>
<P>
"What we should do is to let each nation live by its own values
and by its own message that we all could be proud of," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the world is entering into a new era where the
whole world is connected by economic affairs.
</P>
<P>
"The world is fast becoming one global village," Kissinger
claimed.
</P>
<P>
On the U.S.- Philippine relations, Kissinger said that the
relations between the two countries have not decreased despite the
American withdrawal of its troops from two military bases -- the
Clark air base and the Subic naval base in the Philippines in the
early 1990's. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
