<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Labor Law Approved by South Korean Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 11 (Xinhua) -- A new labor law was approved today
at a cabinet meeting called by Prime Minister Koh Kun and it would
be submitted to President Kim Young-sam for his final approval
before it comes into effect.
</P>
<P>
According to the new labor law adopted by the South Korean
National Assembly late on Monday, multiple unions within an
enterprise are justified, but employers are permitted to stop
paying strikers according to the "no work, no pay" clause.
</P>
<P>
Employers are also permitted to introduce flexible work hours,
but a ceiling of no more than 12 hours is set for total working
hours per day.
</P>
<P>
Sackings will be allowed in two years on grounds of "management
emergency" only.
</P>
<P>
Employers are banned from paying full-time union officials from
2002.
</P>
<P>
The new law was a revised bill to replace a law passed in the
parliament last December by the ruling New Korea Party before the
arrival of the parliament members from opposition parties. The
event sparked the withdrawal of the opposition parties from the
parliament and large-scale strikes organized by the labor unions.
</P>
<P>
Under increasing domestic political pressures, the ruling party
was forced to make a concession to revise the law in exchange for
support from opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
The revised labor law was finally adopted by the parliament
late on Monday with the favorable votes in the parliament from
both the ruling party and two major opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the new law was widely accepted by
employers but the labor unions saw no obvious improvement in the
law. Labor unions asserted that the possibility to call fresh
large-scale strikes could not be ruled out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
