<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Boost Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's leading
industrial centre, is seeking to spur the growth of its
burgeoning foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Mayor Jiang Yiren, in charge of the city's foreign
trade, said Shanghai will try to develop all five areas of foreign
trade-- commodity export, overseas fund application, technology
trade, service trade and sino-foreign economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Exports in Shanghai totalled 13 billion US dollars in 1996,
10.5 percent more than that of 1995. However, growth of export is
restricted by elements such as resources shortage and rising labor
costs.
</P>
<P>
Under the export-enhancement program, the municipal government
gives a shot-in-the arm to the service trade.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that current revenue of Shanghai's service
trade accounts for a mere 12 percent of its total commodity
exports. By contrast, Hong Kong's service trade accounts for an
impressive 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
A top foreign trade official said foreign-funded firms are
expected to export five billion US dollars worth of commodities
this year, up 20 percent over last year. The city also plans to
name 70 varieties of goods its major export commodities, which
will bring in a total of 5.5 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The city aims to boost export of mechanical and electronic
equipment by encouraging local entrepreneurs to invest in or
contract construction projects abroad, said the official, who
forecast a remarkable rise in export of computer softwares and
other hi-tech products.
</P>
<P>
As part of its bid to promote exports, Shanghai plans to form a
batch of large enterprise groups in various fields of foreign
trade, and to build new export commodity manufacturing bases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
