<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ARATS Head Voices Confidence about Future HK-Taiwan Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Tang Shubei, Executive Vice
Chairman of the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Strait
(ARATS), expresses confidence about relations between Taiwan and
Hong Kong after the latter's return to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Tang told a press conference here today that some specific
issues concerning Hong Kong-Taiwan ties after July 1 have already
been properly dealt with, or will soon be.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that Vice Premier Qian Qichen, on behalf of the
central government, has announced seven principles on Hong
Kong-Taiwan ties after July 1, and "we are ready to see that
non-governmental exchanges between Hong Kong and Taiwan are
maintained and developed under the principle of one China."
</P>
<P>
He said Taiwan organizations and personnel in Hong Kong can
remain there after July 1; however, they must follow the "one
China" principle and must not engage in activities that violate
the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region or
activities that go beyond their registered scope of activities.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to see that they make contributions to the
development of relations between Hong Kong and Taiwan, and to Hong
Kong's prosperity and stability," Tang noted.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Hong Kong-Taiwan relations after July 1
will be a special part of relations between the two sides of
the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
Issues that involve cross-strait relations and national
sovereignty will be handled by the central government or the
government of the Hong Kong SAR with authorization from the
central government, with the rest to be handled by the HKSAR
government in accordance with the Basic Law, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
The problem of air links between Hong Kong and Taiwan after
July 1 has been resolved, said Tang.
</P>
<P>
As for sea links between the two places, he said, the
spokespersons of the Taiwan Affairs Office and the Hong Kong and
Macao Affairs Office under the State Council have emphasized that
marine shipping between Hong Kong and Taiwan should also be
conducted under the "one China" principle.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that the central government has made arrangement
for the issue of travel documents for Taiwan residents entering
Hong Kong after July 1, which will be made public in a few months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
