<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Likely to Lose 300,000 Jobs After US GSP Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Thailand might lose more than
314,000 jobs if the United States ends generalized system of
preferences (GSP) tax concessions on Thai exports, the Thai
Commerce Ministry said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
If Thai manufacturers do nothing to improve productivity,
losses in its exports will amount to 5.18 billion baht (207.2
million US dollars), the ministry warned.
</P>
<P>
The ministry made the prediction before the United States
introduce a new GSP program when its existing one is due to expire
on May 30.
</P>
<P>
Thailand emerged as the biggest beneficiary of the US GSP in
the region after the US gradually lifted its GSP privileges for
Malaysia, local newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
Thai electronics exporters said that their exports will be
affected seriously if the US decides to end GSP privileges for
their products.
</P>
<P>
The exporters said that they will lose the price
competitiveness they are enjoying now on the US market.
</P>
<P>
However, the Thai Plastic Industries Association said that Thai
plastic products would remain active on the US market even without
GSP privileges.  
</P>
</TEXT>
