<HEADLINE> Study under Way for Handling Taiwan Hijacker Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- A senior official in charge of
Taiwan affairs said in Beijing today that relevant departments of
the Chinese mainland are studying the issue of a Taiwan hijacker.
</P>
<P>
Tang Shubei, executive vice-chairman of the Association for
Relations across the Taiwan Strait (ARATS), made this announcement
while answering reporters' questions at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
A Taiwan plane was hijacked to the city of Xiamen in east
China's Fujian Province on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Xiamen Airport had taken good, proper care of the hijacked
plane, and provided food and drinks for passengers aboard," said
Tang, adding that the plane, after being refuelled, left Xiamen
for Taiwan at around 6:50 p.m. yesterday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the ARATS has sent missages to the Foundation for
Exchange across the Taiwan Strait in Taiwan twice during this
period to provide the relevant information.
</P>
<P>
A plane hijackers is a criminal offender that should be
repatriated according to the Quemoy Agreement reached between the
ARATS and the Strait Exchange Foundation.
</P>
<P>
"The Taiwanese side agreed in principle that plane hijackers
from the mainland should be repatriated, but fails to abide by the
agreement and has not sent them back up until now," he said.
</P>
<P>
"So the handling of the Taiwan hijacker issue is relatively
complicated. This is all due to the Taiwanese side," he explained.
</P>
<P>
The relevant departments of the Chinese mainland are making
further investigations on the Taiwan hijacker, Tang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Scientist Finds New Way To Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli doctors are using a
remote-control device to help women with atonic bladders to
urinate, a way regarded as a breakthrough in the world, The
Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The device was developed by Dr. Ofer Nativ, a urologist at Bnei
Zion Hospital in Haifa, north Israel.
</P>
<P>
The invention is meant for women who were born without
muscular control of their bladder, or who lost control due to
neurological illnesses or traumatic injury.
</P>
<P>
The device, called the intra-urethral sphincter and pump
prosthesis, draws urine from the bladder using a small pump that
can remain in the woman's body for a month or more.
</P>
<P>
Periodically, the woman holds a cigar-shaped remote-control
device -- which contains a battery -- next to her lower abdomen
to activate a magnet that turns on the pump. When all the urine
has emptied out, the device beeps.
</P>
<P>
The battery is changed every few weeks, and the 2.5 to 6
centimeters silicone tube and pump are changed every four weeks
to three months. In many cases, the patient herself can change
them.
</P>
<P>
"Without this device, women have to undergo the time-consuming,
annoying, embarrassing and limiting procedure of inserting a
catheter into their urethra five or six times a day to drain the
urine," said Nativ.
</P>
<P>
The traditional catheterization is usually done by a specially
trained person, and sometimes by the patient herself. If any
residual urine remains in the bladder, infections or bleeding
could result. Other patients have a stoma leading out of the
abdomen and a urine-collection bag that must be emptied several
times a day, according to Nativ. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
