<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Russian Border Fair Trade Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Harbin, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Border fair trade between
China's Heilongjiang Province and Russia witnessed record-high
growth in 1996, according to latest statistics.
</P>
<P>
The volume of such business topped 350 million US dollars,
more than double the figure of 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to official definition, border fair trade refers to
that trade done within 20 square kilometers from the border at
government-designated markets.
</P>
<P>
The increase was scored after Sino-Russian border trade had
slipped due to policy readjustments between the two governments
and quality problems.
</P>
<P>
In order to encourage border transaction, the Chinese
Government exempted tariffs on items priced below 1,000 yuan
(120.48 US dollars) for each person daily.
</P>
<P>
Another factor was enhanced market supervision on the Chinese
side to ensure the quality of the commodities traded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
