<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chung Ying Street Should Keep Its Name: Deputies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The Chung Ying Street, linking
Shenzhen and Hong Kong, should retain its name after Hong Kong's
return to the motherland in July and be made into a venue for
education in patriotism, two legislators proposed.
</P>
<P>
"Chung Ying" literally means "Sino-British" in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was made by Zhang Lei and Lu Peiyan, both
Guangdong deputies to the Eighth National People's Congress, which
has been in session here since March 1.
</P>
<P>
The 250-m-long and 3.5-m-wide street, where two social systems
coexist, is deemed as an epitome of the modern history of China.
It was a small river before silting turned it into a strip of
grassland.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 99 years ago, Britain forced the Qing government of
China to sign Convention for the Extension of Hong Kong. Ever
since then, the street has remained separated into two parts.
</P>
<P>
Zhang and Lu proposed that the Shenzhen city and the future
government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region keep the
name of Chung Ying Street, to let future generations of the
Chinese people bear in mind the painful page in Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
They also proposed that a "Chung Ying Street Museum" be
established and made into a venue for education in patriotism.
</P>
<P>
Related departments have already begun to study the proposal,
it is learned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
