<HEADLINE> Kissinger to Address Top Philippine Policy Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Former United States National
Security Adviser and Secretary of State Henry Kissinger will
address Wednesday here a group of top Filipino policy makers on
global implications of Southeast Asian unification.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency reported today that Kissinger's
vision on the Southeast Asian unification could be a major policy
input to policies that the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) is currently working on as it prepares for its 30th
founding anniversary in August this year.
</P>
<P>
Grouping Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam, the ASEAN now hopes to advance
its "ASEAN-10" goal for the year of 2000 to this year.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN is expected to include by August this year the last
three Southeast Asian countries into its fold -- Cambodia, Laos
and Myanmar, the Philippine News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Kissinger arrived here Monday for a series of major policy
speaking with various groups from the government, the academia and
the private business sector of the country.
</P>
<P>
Today, he was due to receive an honorary doctorate by the
University of the Philippines at its Diliman Campus in Quezon
City, Metro Manila, after addressing a special student convocation
at the state university.
</P>
<P>
Kissinger is scheduled to call on Philippine President Fidel
Ramos at the Presidential Palace Thursday. The president is
expected to be home then from his 10-day visit to South Asia and
the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
