<HEADLINE> Uganda Denies Sudan Accusation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Uganda denied yesterday Sudan's
accusation about its involment in internal conflict in southern
Sudan, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Medi Kaggwa, the State Minister in Uganda's President's Office
for Political Affairs, told ''the New Vision'', ''Uganda
(Ugandans) is not in Sudan and neither do we want to intend to be
there.''
</P>
<P>
An official statement of the Sudanese armed forces broadcasted
later Sunday said that the Ugandan armed forces attacked Sudanese
border town of Kaya earlier Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Local media said the attackers are the rebels of Sudan People's
Liberation Army (SPLA). The latest news reaching here said the
Sudanese rebels were 10 kilometers away from Yei yesterday, an important
garrison city in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The loud crossfires were heard in northwestern Ugandan city of
Arua, some 77 kilometers south of the Uganda-Sudan border.
</P>
<P>
Shaban Bantariza, the Public Relation Officer of the Fourth
Division of the Ugandan army, told local journalists in northern
city of Gulu, ''we are only at borders waiting for rebels.''
</P>
<P>
There are two Ugandan rebel groups in the area affected by the
bloody conflict -- the West Nile Bank Front (WNBF) and the Uganda
National Rescue Front, Part Two (UNRF ii). Reports reaching here
said the two rebel groups were covering the Sudanese army in its
fighting against SPLA rebels.
</P>
<P>
At least 86 officers and soldiers of the Sudanese army and Ugandan
rebels were killed in the fighting since earlier Sunday, reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Amama Mbabazi, Ugandan State Minister for Defence, confirmed to
local English newspaper ''the Crusader'' that Major General Mugisha
Muntu, the Ugandan Army Commander, shifted to Gulu to monitor the
developemnt in southern Sudan. The army commander is likely to stay
in the north ''as long as his presence was required,'' Amama said.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA has been fighting for independence of Christian-dominated
south from the Moslem dominated north.
</P>
<P>
Eriya Kateaya, the First Deputy Prime Minister and the Minister of
Foreign Affairs of Uganda, said the planned Iran-brokered
Uganda-Sudan talk will be held in Kampala on Friday as scheduled.
enditem

=03110837

=03110844
NNNN
16:45 16:45 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
