<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Stops Showing of Story of Filipino Overseas Maid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today ordered to defer the public showing of a controversial film
about the suffering of a Filipino overseas contract worker.
</P>
<P>
Ramos sent an urgent fax message to the chairman of the Movie
and Television Regulation and Classification Board to stop showing
"The Sarah Balabagan Story" from Bahrain, the last leg of his
10-day visit to South Asia and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He ordered the board to "take all necessary actions" to defer
the showing of the movie in an anticipation that the film would
have an extreme negative impact on the relations between the
Philippines and the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ramos also asked the Department of Justice to study
the possibility of filing a temporary restraining order on the
movie on the ground of national interest.
</P>
<P>
The movie is about a teenage Filipino Muslim girl who was
sentenced to death for killing a UAE national after she defended
her womanhood.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government, particularly President Ramos asked
the UAE government to save Balabagan from execution.
</P>
<P>
In response to the appeal that also included an appeal from
various world organizations to spare the young Filipino girl from
the death sentence, the UAE commuted the sentence to a few years
imprisonment and eventually released her from prison last year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Undersecretary Leonides Caday earlier wrote a
memo to President Ramos, recommending the stopping of the film
from being shown to the public.
</P>
<P>
Caday said the movie contains some portion in which the UAE
will resent like the rape scene which was not consummated but
displayed the killing of Mr. Baloushi, the UAE national killed by
Balabagan.
</P>
<P>
The UAE government has already warned that the showing of the
film may have a negative effect on the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency said the showing of the film might
also affect the life of another Filipino facing death penalty in
the UAE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Crisis Remains Despite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The current Israeli-Palestinian
crisis has remained despite a high-level meeting Monday night
between Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Palestinian
Culture and Information Minister Yasser Abed Rabbo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the 90-minute meeting held in Tel Aviv, Rabbo
said the two sides failed to bridge the huge gap on the issues of
Israel's decision on further troop pullbacks, its plan to build
Har Homa neighborhood and to close four Palestinian offices in
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) hopes to gain about 30
percent of the West Bank rather than the Israeli-decided 9
percent in every stage of the three-phase further pullbacks, and
it is demanding Israel to cancel the new plan to build 6,500
Jewish apartments in Har Homa of southeastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"There is a crisis, and the crisis is becoming worse and
worse, because the agreements should be accepted and the
settlements and confiscation of land should stop," Rabbo said.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai, on his part, acknowledged the clear gap existing
between the two sides. But he defended Israel's decision on the
scope of further troop pullbacks and the plan to build the Har
Homa neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
He called on the PNA to continue the peace process and
refrain from violence despite the current crisis. "I suggest to
Mr. Rabbo and the Palestinian (National) Authority to continue to
do the best efforts together to move on quite a lot of subjects
that can improve the life of the Palestinians," he said.
</P>
<P>
With tension mounting, clashes broke out late Monday between
Israeli troops and Palestinian demonstrators in the volatile
West Bank town of Hebron, during which 11 Palestinians were
injured.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators were trying to prevent Israeli bulldozers to
clear the ground to build a road connecting the nearby Kiryat
Arab settlement and the Jewish quarter of Hebron. The area has
been declared a closed military zone.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai warned that violence was "too dangerous" and could
destroy the peace process, adding he had asked Rabbo to send the
message to PNA President Yasser Arafat to do his best to prevent
violence.
</P>
<P>
Arafat warned earlier Monday that the peace march was in a
"real crisis" because of Israel's clear violation of the peace
accords. He called Israel's decisions on further pullbacks, on
Har Homa settlement construction and closure of the Palestinian
offices in East Jerusalem "tricks and conspiracies" against the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
In a sign apparently indicating the depth of the current
crisis, Israel Radio reported today that Arafat has refused to
answer telephone calls from Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu in the past days.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who left Monday for a two-day visit to Russia, has
instructed Foreign Minister David Levy to continue contacts with
the Palestinian side. 
</P>
