<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pretoria's Munitoria Fire Not Arson, Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The fire which destroyed half of
Pretoria's City Council Administration complex, Munitoria, was caused
by a malfunctioning electrical component in a light fitting and not by
arson, fire investigators said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the forensic investigations, the fire started last
Monday evening when bitumen in the light's ballast, which used to
boost the voltage of the fluorescent light when it is turned on,
melted and caught fire, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Forensic investigator David Klatzow said the heat of the meltdown
would have pushed the flammable material up to near ignition
temperature and was set alight by a sperk from a short-circuit caused
by the meltdown.
</P>
<P>
The fire spread through the ceiling void (the space between floors)
from the basement into the main building, where it destroyed most of
the western section, causing millions of Rand's damage to the complex.
</P>
<P>
The bitumen, which is used as an insulator, would have dripped into
a drip tray, making the fire almost impossible to detect, said
Klatzow, adding it could have taken 30 to 90 minutes for the bitumen
to melt before catching fire.
</P>
<P>
However, he ruled out arson was the cause for the fire.
</P>
<P>
Negligence in maintaining the electrical fittings was also
dismissed by Klatzow and Kobus Strydom from the Council for Scientific
and Industrial Research, another member of the investigation team.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, fire department investigator Captain Andre de Beer said
his team had been able to pinpoint where the fire began from
witnesses's accounts, the damage to ceilings, and how the fire vented
itself.
</P>
<P>
Once the fire had spread into the ceiling void and into a
staircase, it was extremely difficult to stop, added Klatzow.
</P>
<P>
The fire flared up again twice last week but was quickly put out
each time. enditem

=03110819

=03110825
NNNN
16:26 16:27 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
