<HEADLINE> HKSAR Chief Executive's Office Reinforced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The Chief Executive's Office of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) announced
today that Michael Suen and Irene Yau will be seconded to the
Office.
</P>
<P>
Suen, who is presently Secretary for Home Affairs of the Hong
Kong government, will take up the post of Secretary for Policy
Co-ordination in the new office; Yau, now director of Information
Services of the Hong Kong government, will be the director of
Information and Public Relations in the new office.
</P>
<P>
Both Suen and Yau will take up their new posts tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Elsie Leung, Secretary of Justice, is already
assisting the Chief Executive on a range of legal issues. She will
officially join the Chief Executive's Office on April 1.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, Chief Executive of the HKSAR, said: "I am very
pleased with the additional staffing support which is much needed
as work builds up in the lead up to the handover."
</P>
<P>
He said that Suen is the most senior of the Policy Secretaries
and will bring with him a wealth of experience.
</P>
<P>
Tung also welcomed Yau's secondment, saying that "Mrs Yau and
her team will be of immense value to the Office as we step up our
publicity and public relations efforts."
</P>
<P>
"There is a lot of work to be done. With additional staffing
support, we should be able to move full steam ahead," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tung's office said officers who are seconded to the Chief
Executive's Office take temporary leave of absence from the Hong
Kong government and will work under the direction of, and be
accountable to, the Chief Executive. The secondment will end on
July 1, 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
