<HEADLINE> Overseas Firms Show Interest in Shenzhen's Bridge Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Overseas companies have shown
interest in Shenzhen's planned highway bridge across the sea
linking the city with Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
C.P. Yu, chairman of the board of Kumagai Gumi (H.K.) Limited,
and Cheng Yu-tung, chairman of the board of the New World
Development Co. Ltd of Hong Kong, together paid a special visit to
Mayor Li Zibin on Monday and expressed their wish to participate
in Shenzhen's major construction projects including the sea bridge.
</P>
<P>
The two businessmen expressed their willingness to form a
consortium responsible for the finance and construction of the
bridge and related support roads and facilities, to ensure that
the "western thoroughfare" project will be completed as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, Shenzhen plans to build a bridge
across the sea from Dongjiaotou at Shekou and join it with Hong
Kong's Trunk Route No.3 near Yuen Long.
</P>
<P>
The entire project is expected to cost 2.9 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Other overseas companies have also made similar bids to
construct the project, said local officials.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong businessmen have invested seven billion U.S. dollars
in Shenzhen, Guangdong Province. They also plan to invest six
billion yuan to build high-rise apartments in the city's Futian
New Area where 400,000 sq m of land have been leased.
</P>
<P>
Kumagai Gumi (H.K.) Limited has made investment for the
construction of Shenzhen's highest mansion and has also undertaken
development in Yangpu in southern China's Hainan Province.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Yu-tung's company has invested mainly in highway and
bridge construction projects outside Shenzhen, including the No.2
highway bridge across the Yangtze River at Wuhan in central
China's Hubei Province. 
</P>
