<HEADLINE> East China's Province Strengthens Investment Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 11 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang Province
this year plans to rearrange the investment structure to secure
sustained economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the provincial economic planning authorities
revealed that the investment in fixed assets this year will be
limited to 185.5 billion yuan, with growth rate slightly less than
last year.
</P>
<P>
The capital is planned to be poured into agriculture,
infrastructure construction, and industries that could drive
future economic growth, as well as cultural, scientific and
educational fields.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang in recent years gradually adjusted the investment
structure and diverted the precious assets to needy sectors. An
increasing proportion of funds has been injected to energy,
transport and telecommunications projects, fields long considered
bottlenecks for local economic development.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to build an expressway linking Hangzhou, the
provincial capital, with Shanghai. The second-phase of Qinshan
Nuclear Power Plant, Yuxi Hydroelectric Power Plant, an airport in
Zhoushan Island, to name a few, are scheduled to start initial
construction.
</P>
<P>
The local government will establish measures to supervise use
of capital, reducing blind investment to a minimum.  
</P>
</TEXT>
