<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Relocates Over 700 Factories From Downtown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 11 (Xinhua) -- China's largest city has
relocated over 700 industrial firms from the urban districts in a
move to reduce pollution and make room for the development of the
service trade.
</P>
<P>
The city, pledging to become an international economic,
financial and trade center, plans to make large-scale
readjustments to the existing 3,000-plus factories.
</P>
<P>
Of this group, more than 2,000 will be moved to the suburban
areas or be turned into service firms.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the 700 relocated factories,
including textiles and chemical companies, are serious polluters,
and their removal has left a three sq km-space suitable for the
development of real estate, trade and banking industries.
</P>
<P>
The city government has drafted preferential policies for the
purpose. Local unprofitable firms see this as a good opportunity
for future development, while many overseas companies have been
engaged in the development of the former sites.
</P>
<P>
The readjustments will be completed before the year 2010, and
by then, Shanghai will see a five sq km-central office block, a 30
sq km-central commercial area and a 70 sq km downtown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
