<HEADLINE> U.S. Hails Mexico's Appointment of New Anti-drug Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
applauded Mexico's appointment of new top anti-drug officer,
saying it would help dispel doubt about President Bill Clinton's
decision to certify Mexico as an ally in the fight against drugs.
</P>
<P>
Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo named Mariano Herran
Salvatti, a lawyer, to replace former anti-drug chief, Gen. Jesus
Gutierrez Rebollo, who was arrested on charges of accepting pay
from Mexico's top drug lord.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said the
nomination should be welcomed by the U.S. Congress, which has been
critical of Clinton's move, saying Mexico lacked sincerity and
capability in combating drugs.
</P>
<P>
"We think it's a highly significant appointment which ought to
be welcomed by the detractors of our president's policy," Burns
said. "We have absolute trust and confidence in President
Zedillo."
</P>
<P>
Burns hoped the announcement "will convince those in Congress
and those around the country and perhaps even in our own
hemisphere who have any doubts that President Zedillo's commitment
to wage the war against narcotics is genuine."
</P>
<P>
Last week, the International Relations Committee of U.S. House
of Representatives voted 27-5 to overturn Clinton's certification
that Mexico was fully cooperating in the battle against drugs.
The full House is to vote later this week.
</P>
<P>
A similar measure has been introduced in the Senate and its
Foreign Relations Committee has scheduled a hearing on the issue
for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton today also defended his decision to certify Mexico and
vowed to convince the U.S. Congress to back his position.
</P>
<P>
"I'm going to do my best to persuade the Congress that we're
right," Clinton said at a joint White House news conference with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
