<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Nepal's New Prime Minister Chand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Before being appointed prime
minister of Nepal's new government by King Birendra Monday night,
Lokendra Bahadur Chand had been prime minister twice during the
partyless Panchayat era which ended in the country in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Chand, parliamentary leader of the National Democratic Party
(RPP), is expected to form his cabinet and take the oath later
today with the participation of the Communist Party of Nepal
(United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML) and the Nepal Goodwill Party
(NSP).
</P>
<P>
Born in a landlord family in far western hilly district of
Baitadi in 1940, Chand received higher education in the capital
and the neighboring India by completing his two bachelor's degrees
of arts and law.
</P>
<P>
He began his political career in 1968 when being elected a
deputy representing his home village in the then Panchayat
legislature of the Baitadi district, nearly 400 km from Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
He was elected to the national Panchayat legislature, or the
National Assembly, six years later and became vice chairman of the
legislature in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Chand was appointed prime minister for the first time in July
1983 by King Birendra under the recommendation of the National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
It seemed that he was destined to become the last prime
minister under the Panchayat system, which was introduced in 1960
following a ban on political parties, when he was again appointed
to the post in 1990.
</P>
<P>
King Birendra abolished the partyless legislature and
reinstated the multi-party parliamentary system in the same year
amid a nationwide people's movement jointly led by the Nepali
Congress (NC) party and the Communist party.
</P>
<P>
Chand formed his RPP party, whose membership mostly comprises
former Panchayat members, in 1990 and the RPP party won 19 seats
of the 205-seat lower house in the 1994 mid-term elections.
</P>
<P>
He managed to bring down a three-party government led by NC
leader Sher Bahadur Deuba last week through joining hands with the
main opposition the CPN-UML, which has 90 MPs in the house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yu Dafu Collection Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 11 (Xinhua) -- A collection of the works of Yu
Dafu (1896-1945), one of modern China's most celebrated authors,
has been published.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts say that the 1.3 million-word book, collecting
all the articles written by Yu and available documents related to
his life, is the most reliable and complete chronological life
story of Yu ever published.
</P>
<P>
Born in 1896 in east China's Zhejiang Province, Yu became a
major promoter of democratic literature in the 1920s. After the
breaking out of the Anti-Japanese War (1937-1945), Yu, active in
the save-the-country movement, exiled himself to southeast Asia
where he was killed by Japanese soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Yu was famous for his exquisite style of writing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
