<HEADLINE> Memorial Hall for Famous Monk to Be Built in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The former residence of Buddhist
monk Hong Yi (1880-1942) in Tianjin will be renovated into a
memorial hall.
</P>
<P>
The monk, named Li Shutong during his laymanship, was born in
in 1880 in a 150-year-old compound with houses around a square
courtyard in Tianjin, where he spent his childhood and
adolescence.
</P>
<P>
After learning Western Arts in Japan for five years, he went to
Hangzhou city in east China's Zhejiang Province in 1910 to teach
arts and music in two normal colleges, and continued to pursue
studies on the West.
</P>
<P>
In 1918 he became a monk in a temple in Hangzhou.
</P>
<P>
His former residence in Tianjin was listed as relic under city
protection in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The memorial hall is expected to be completed in 2000, on the
occasion of the 120th birthday of the monk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
