<HEADLINE> Shanghai Hosts Coin Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest city,
recently held the country's first coin auction in which coin
connoisseurs traded more than 1,000 coins of different eras.
</P>
<P>
The oldest coin auctioned at the fair -- a silver coin cast by
an emperor of China's Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) and circulated in
Tibet -- can be dated back to 1794.
</P>
<P>
A silver dollar, which was cast in 1930, said to be one of only
20 remaining in existence, was auctioned off at 500,000 yuan
(60,240 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The auction attracted 120 coin collectors from China, the
United States, Singapore, and Hong Kong. The auction's
transaction volume was 5.02 million yuan. 
