<HEADLINE> U.S. Welcomes Albanian Political Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Washington today welcomed a
political agreement between Albanian President Sali Berisha and
the opposition to form an interim coalition government ahead of
early elections in June, a U.S. State Department spokesman
announced.
</P>
<P>
"We join our European partners in welcoming the agreement
between President Berisha and the opposition in Albania, " State
Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said.
</P>
<P>
"We now strongly urge all parties in Albania to implement this
agreement, to implement the amnesty, the cease-fire, and to work
towards the formation of the new government," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, a new prime minister will be named by
Berisha and the deputy prime minister will be appointed by the
opposition. The rest of the ministerial posts will be divided
equally between Berisha's Democratic Party and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Berisha was forced to agree to set up the interim government
following weeks of unrest in the country and a week of fighting
between the military and rebels demanding his resignation in the
wake of the collapse of pyramid investment schemes.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people lost their life savings and blamed Berisha
for allowing the schemes. Weeks of street protests turned violent
10 days ago when rebels looted army depots for weapons and started
fighting government forces.
</P>
<P>
The government last week declared a state of emergency, but the
violence continued, centered around the key southern town of
Vlore. An estimated 40 people have died in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today rebels from Vlore signed an Italian-brokered
agreement with Berisha to lay down their arms.
</P>
<P>
Eight representatives of the rebels in Vlore signed a
declaration on an Italian warship to hand in weapons in the hands
of ordinary people and to ensure public order and restore normal
administration to the town.
</P>
<P>
Berisha, who has also agreed to start lifting the state of
emergency, said an amnesty would be granted to anyone handing in
weapons before the end of the week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
