<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Government Urges Senate to Pass Chemical Weapons Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government said today
it will continue attempts to persuade the Senate to ratify the
Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC) by April 29 despite threats by
the treaty's opponents to use every effort to block it.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to maintain this issue as one of our most
important congressional issues, in fact, one of our most important
foreign policy issues in 1997," U.S. State Department spokesman
Nicholas Burns told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Jesse Helms, Chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, pledged to block the ratification unless the
convention was substantially modified.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the administration makes the modifications I am
demanding, the CWC will not leave my committee, " the Republican
senator declared.
</P>
<P>
If the United States does not ratify the CWC by April 29 when
it is due to go into effect, it cannot participate in the
committee that will draw up the treaty's rules of implementation.
</P>
<P>
Burns said there were strategic reasons for ratifying the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
"If we're not part of it (the committee), we leave ourselves
defenseless with no way to help write the rules of
implementation," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
"By refusing to ratify, we won't have chemical weapons
ourselves, we won't be able to influence the international debate
to limit countries that do have them, " said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The CWC, which bans the production and stockpiling of all
chemical weapons has been ratified by more than 60 countries
including China, enough for the treaty to take effect on April 29
with or without the U.S. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Diplomats Lose Immunity from Parking Fines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 10 (Xinhua) -- There was uproar in the
United Nations today when diplomats were told today that they
 would no longer be exempt from paying parking fines.
</P>
<P>
Starting next month, diplomats who fail to clear up their
tickets within 12 months would lose their license plates until
they paid up, U.S. and New York city officials said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the U.N. Committee on relations with the host
country, which deals with problems affecting the diplomatic
community, American United Nations Envoy Bill Richardson said:
"Consistent with the obligation of all to obey local laws,
beginning on April 1, the owners of diplomatic vehicles which have
parked illegally will be expected to either pay or otherwise
adjudicate all parking summonses received."
</P>
<P>
Objections were raised immediately by representatives of
Russia, France, Britain, China, Spain, Honduras, Costa Rica and
other countries.
</P>
<P>
Several diplomats said the rules were being imposed without
proper consultation and called for the establishment of a working
group to study the matter.
</P>
<P>
Others complained that their vehicles had been deliberately
ticketed, even if parked in a reserved spot, and that unauthorized
vehicles in a diplomatic parking space were rarely towed or
ticketed.
</P>
<P>
After listing numerous annoying experiences with New York
police on the parking issue, a Russian diplomat concluded that the
New York city was not friendly to the diplomatic corps and that
the United Nations should move its headquarters to another place.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe, a large-scale anti-UN campaign is a signal that now,
after 50 years, the city has grown tired of the United Nations,
fed up with its own problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
If this was the case, it was not the parking issue which should
be considered, he said. "What we should look into, then, are
offers from other cities to host the United Nations headquarters."
</P>
<P>
But Bill Richardson argued the U.S. State Department had
determined that the new policy and program were "consistent with
international law as well as with the host country's obligations
to the United Nations and the United Nations community in New
York."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
