<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Way Found to Modify Ultra-tiny Structures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have developed a
method of modifying the outermost surface of materials which will
open the door for new applications in computing, microelectronics
and the storage of information.
</P>
<P>
The system brings ions in for a "soft-landing" on surfaces,
providing a new way to trap and study ions and modify the outmost
layer, says a newsletter from Purdue University.
</P>
<P>
Ions are electrically charged atoms, or groups of atoms.
</P>
<P>
The new technique is also outlined in the latest issue of the
Science journal.
</P>
<P>
"This not only allows us to preserve the ions for future use,
but also allows us to modify the surface of a material in a way
that is reversible." says Graham Cooks, professor of Chemistry at
Purdue, and chief researcher of the team.
</P>
<P>
Generally scientists use instruments called mass spectrometers
to study ions. However, ions are only stable while in flight. When
they hit a surface, crash landings take a toll on the tiny
structures, making it impossible to preserve them or deposit them
onto a surface without destroying them.
</P>
<P>
Even the most successful instruments can trap ions for only a
few seconds.
</P>
<P>
Cooks and his team developed a way to "parachute" ions onto a
surface and bring them in for a soft landing. "Our study shows for
the first time that polyatomic ions can be transferred from the
gas phase to a surface and held there for periods of days," cooks
said.
</P>
<P>
First, they made gold surfaces covered with a single layer of
organic molecules called fluoracarbons, which stood vertically
like flagpoles from the surface and were strongly bonded to the
gold. Then they attached bulky groups of trimethylsilicon
molecules to the end of each ion to slow its landing and ensure
that it did not hit the gold surface.
</P>
<P>
Once the ions landed -- wedging between the fluorocarbon
structures, the fluorocarbons served as shields to keep the
chemically reactive particles from interacting with the gold
surface or with molecules in the air.
</P>
<P>
"This experiment allows virtually any chemical species to be
generated in a mass spectrometer as an ion, and injected into a
surface," Cooks says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
