<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lanka-Kuwait Joint
Commission (SLKJC), which was set up at the end of last year, held
its first meeting here Monday evening, according to Trade Ministry
sources today.
</P>
<P>
Trade between Sri Lanka and Kuwait has shown remarkable
progress over the past several years, the sources quoted Trade
Minister Kingsley Wickremaratne as saying at the opening session
of the SLKJC first meeting.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that trade with Kuwait had brought Sri Lanka
Rs 720 million (12.8 million U.S. dollars) in foreign exchange and
Sri Lanka's main export item tea enjoyed a market share of 42
percent of the total tea market in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
They said that the two countries had been linked in trade over
centuries and the current meeting would help renew tie-ups, mutual
understanding and respect.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's exports to Sri Lanka reached 10 million U.S. dollars
in 1995 and in the first nine months of 1996 increased to 11.5
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Sri Lankan workers are employed in Kuwait,
according to the sources.  
</P>
