<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Members Call for More Organ Donations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Eight medical experts in China's
top advisory body today raised a proposal calling on more people
in China to donate their organs and bodies posthumously to save
the life of patients suffering organic exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Zheng Falei with the Chinese Academy of Medical Sciences,
and seven other members of the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), which is in
its fifth annual session here, have followed the example of some
Chinese legislators, who set forth a proposal on posthumous organ
donation several days ago.
</P>
<P>
All eight members are noted medical experts, including two
academicians of the Chinese Academy of Engineering and
vice-presidents of several major hospitals.
</P>
<P>
"Donation of organs and bodies after death is a embodiment of
lofty moral integrity, and a concrete expression of the ethical
and cultural progress of the mankind," they noted in the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Describing organic exhaustion as one of the most serious
threats that endangers the people's health and life, the experts
acknowledged that organ transplant has become a popular means of
rescuing human life in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that to date, more than 400,000 people around
the world have received transplanted organs, and 300,000 of them
now have transplanted kidneys. Moreover, marrow, heart, liver and
other organs can also be transplanted.
</P>
<P>
In spite of marked progress scored across China in this field
since the early 1970s, organ transplant still falls far behind
that in the developed countries, owing mainly to a lack of donors.
</P>
<P>
"The state should step up the ethical education on organ
transplant in whole society, and increased efforts should be made
to spread scientific knowledge in public," the experts suggested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
