<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Thai government agencies
concerned are working on a plan to check cheating behaviors during
the country's university entrance examinations, a senior Thai
official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
To prevent the practice this year, the Police Department will
cooperate with University Affairs Ministry officials in detecting
the movement of suspected gangs, said Pramote Chotemongkhol,
deputy permanent secretary of the University Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Post and Telegraph Office has also agreed to lend its
mobile units to help detect electronic signals sent by the gangs,
Pramote said.
</P>
<P>
Details of the plan will be kept secret, Pramote added.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that numerous incidents of cheating
occurred over the past 10 years in the country, but few people
were arrested for the practice.
</P>
<P>
Gangs usually directed students sitting in the examination to
answer questions through their special electronic signaling
devices.
</P>
<P>
Customers were usually charged about 25,000 baht (1,000 U.S.
dollars) each and the amount can be higher for popular
specialties.  
