<HEADLINE> North American Countries to Continue Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Mexico will head the recovery
rate among the three North American countries from their
recession-hit economies, at least until 1998, a trinational report
said today
</P>
<P>
Mexico's GNP is expected to grow more than four percent through
1997 and 1998, much higher than its northern neighbors of Canada
and the United States, said the report by the United States-Canada
Conference Board and the Center of Economic Studies of the Private
Sector in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's gross domestic product (GDP) was expected to grow 4.8
percent this year and 5.2 percent in 1998. Mexico was still
recovering from the "dramatic plunge" that followed the
devaluation of the pesos in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The U.S' GDP growth, stimulated by low interest rates, strong
consumption and confidence in the business sector, was projected
at 2.9 percent in 1997 and 2.1 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Canada's GNP, driven more by the exporting sector than by its
internal situation, would grow by 2.9 percent in 1997 and 2.7
percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that this would be the first year since
1994 in which the three north American countries' domestic
economies grew significantly, but warned that their trade balances
and inflation might threaten growth.
</P>
<P>
The three countries would face growing trade deficits in 1997
and 1998, a fact that could be more complicated due to a possible
hike in U.S. domestic interest rates and a slight rebound in
inflation, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Canada, the U.S. and Mexico make up the North American Free
Trade Agreement which was launched on January 1, 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
