<HEADLINE> Ukraine Minister Looks In On NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's Foreign Minister Gennady
Udovenko will visit NATO's headquarters in Brussels on March 20,
to seek political support from the military bloc.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko announced the visit himself at a press here today. He
said he would discuss broadening cooperation with the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization's Secretary General, Javier Solana,
during his visit.
</P>
<P>
NATO should provide Ukraine with political support because the
former Soviet republic, having given up its nuclear weapons, was
playing an important role in maintaining Europe's security,
Udovenko said.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine was not a member of NATO, so the fifth article of the
NATO charter could not apply to Ukraine, Udovenko said. The fifth
article says when a member is threatened, other NATO members will
offer their collective support.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko said he would also discuss with Solana the draft
agreement of special partnership, submitted by Ukraine, which he
hoped would be signed with NATO before or during NATO's summit in
July, in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
NATO was formally founded in August, 1949, and now has 16
member states. 
