<HEADLINE> Forest Contraction Concerns World Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The Food and Agricultural
Organization (FAO) of the United Nations has expressed grave
concern over fast encroachment upon forests worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Every year, 11.3 million hectares of forest are destroyed,
the FAO said in a report submitted to a conference of its
forestry committee, which opened in Rome today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 65.1 million hectares of forests was devastated
between 1990 and 1995, 56.3 million hectares, or 86 percent, of
it being in developing countries, said the 200-page report.
</P>
<P>
Man-made destruction, including over-felling and arson, was the
major cause of the contraction of forests, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that there was 3.5 billion hectares of forests
in the world in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
