<HEADLINE> Chinese, American Sailors Shake Hands in Pearl Harbor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONOLULU, March 10 (Xinhua) -- American and Chinese sailors
gave each other guided tours of their ship decks today in Pearl
Harbor where Chinese naval vessels are on a courtesy call.
</P>
<P>
The Harbin, a guided missile destroyer and the flag ship of the
visiting Chinese vessel group, was open to American sailors. The
4,200 ton ship was commissioned in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chinese sailors visited USS Ingersoll, an 8,200-ton
versatile multi-mission destroyer designed primarily for
anti-submarine warfare.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and American sailors seemed to have many questions to
ask each other. But communicating was difficult because very few
understood each other's language.
</P>
<P>
An American sailor who acted as interpretor for the Chinese
group, had to turn to a small dictionary for help, while the
Chinese sailors found the little English they had learned back at
home inadequate.
</P>
<P>
However, crew members from both sides agreed it was a learning
experience and they were interested in how other side run things.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, a group of Chinese sailors visited the USS
Arizona, a warship sunk during the Japanese bombing of Pearl
Harbor on December 7, 1941 and which is now a memorial to
more than 1,000 U.S. soldiers perished during the attack.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese naval group will stay here until March 13 and then
head for San Diego, a U.S. mainland port that Chinese naval ships
have never visited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
