<HEADLINE> NPC Session Holds Fifth Plenum (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The Fifth Session of the Eighth
National People's Congress (NPC), China's legislature, held its
fifth plenary meeting here today, with legislators hearing work
reports of the Supreme People's Court and the Supreme People's
Procuratorate.
</P>
<P>
The plenary meeting was presided over by Lei Jieqiong,
executive chairman of the meeting and vice-chairman of the NPC
Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Ren Jianxin, president of the Supreme People's Court, made a
report on the court's work to the legislators.
</P>
<P>
"In 1996, the first year of the Ninth Five-Year Plan period
(1996-2000), under the leadership of the Party and supervision of
the people's congresses, courts at all levels across the country,
including special courts such as military and maritime tribunals,
had accepted and heard over 5.26 million cases of first instance,
15.82 percent more than in the previous year," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Among all these criminal, civil, economic, administrative and
maritime cases, more than 5.23 million had been concluded, a 15.53
percent increase over 1995, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The courts have played a positive role in maintaining social
stability and safeguarding the smooth development of reforms,
opening up and socialist modernization drive through its trial
work," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the major tasks for courts in 1997, he said that
the new situation has set forth still higher demands on the work
of the people's courts.
</P>
</TEXT>
