<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Members Favor Proposal on Chongqing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Members of China's top advisory
body considered it a feasible proposal to upgrade Chongqing to a
centrally-administered municipality.
</P>
<P>
Though these members have no right to vote on the proposal,
experts and scholars among the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National Committee, which is
having its session here, expressed their keen interest in what
they called "an important strategy which will be of vital
importance to the development of China's vast interior areas as
well as nationwide economic advances."
</P>
<P>
The proposal has been submitted to the Fifth Session of the
Eighth National People's Congress (NPC) for deliberation.
</P>
<P>
Elevating Chongqing will benefit the building of the Three
Gorges Project, especially the resettlement of one million people
necessitated by the project, said Pan Jiazheng, academician of the
Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a bad idea to separate Sichuan, which is too big, "
said the well-known dam expert.
</P>
<P>
China at present has three centrally-administered
municipalities, namely Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin. On the 14th
of this month, NPC deputies will vote on the proposal to establish
a Chongqing Municipality --the fourth one.
</P>
<P>
In China's Yangtze River Valley development strategy, Shanghai
is often likened to the "dragon head" and Chongqing the "dragon
tail." "How can the dragon move when the dragon tail remain
still?" asked one CPPCC member.
</P>
<P>
Only by building a major economic center can the southwest and
northwest free themselves from poverty, said Zhai Shijing, a
research fellow from the Shanghai Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
While voicing their agreement to the proposal to build
Chongqing into an economic and industrial center, some top
advisors also expressed concern about whether Chongqing can match
the other three municipalities in cultural, scientific and
technological strength.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Fuyu, a senior engineer from the Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications, expressed belief that Chongqing has a solid
foundation in scientific and technological research strength, that
in the weapons industry and the conversion of military
technologies to civilian use, in particular. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Session Holds Fifth Plenum (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"1997 is a year of great importance in the history of China's
development, and the resumption of the exercise of sovereignty
over Hong Kong and the convocation of the 15th Party national
congress are two major events drawing worldwide attention," he
noted. "Therefore, we must maintain social stability and keep a
sustained, rapid and sound development for the economy."
</P>
<P>
The major tasks he listed for 1997 include making unswerving
and unremitting efforts to carry out the "strike hard" campaign,
continuing to seriously punish criminals of embezzlement and
bribery, adjusting economic relations and protecting the
legitimate rights and interests of citizens and legal persons in
accordance with law, improving judicial competence, and making
every effort to build a high-quality contingent of judges.
</P>
<P>
This year, he said, Chinese courts at all levels would carry
work forward at the behest of Comrade Deng Xiaoping, hold high the
banner of Deng's theory of building socialism with Chinese
characteristics, adhere to the Party's basic line, and, under the
leadership of the Party Central Committee with Comrade Jiang Zemin
at the core and the supervision of the people's congresses,
upgrade the trial work onto a new level, so as to serve reforms,
development and stability, and safeguard and promote a coordinated
development of socialist material and ethical-cultural progress.
</P>
<P>
In a work report to the legislators, Zhang Siqing, chief
procurator of the Supreme People's Procuratorate, said that during
the past year, procuratorial organs across the country had scored
all-round progress in various aspects of their work.
</P>
<P>
"We have resolutely investigated and handled major cases of
embezzlement, bribery, and abuse of power to serve one's friends
or relatives that involved government functionaries, dealt hard
blows at serious criminal activities, and made every effort to
strengthen supervision on law enforcement," he noted.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, he said, Chinese procuratorial organs at all levels
had filed to investigate more than 61,000 criminal cases of
embezzlement, bribery, misappropriation of public funds, and huge
assets with unidentified sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
