<HEADLINE> Village of Businesswomen in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 11 (Xinhua) -- A remote village in north
China's Hebei Province is now famous as the "village of
businesswomen".
</P>
<P>
Eighty-five percent of female laborers in the Beiyuanzi Village
are engaged in business.
</P>
<P>
With population of 3,197, the village was once a rustic town in
the mountains, where cooking and taking care of babies was
considered to be a woman's primary role.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980's, when policies of "reform and opening up" were
enforced in this small village, women began to take jobs as men do.
</P>
<P>
The local women's association and government organizations
injected massive aid in the form of preferential policies and
loans.
</P>
<P>
Now a contingent of businesswomen have entered the market, each
of them enjoying per capita income of more than 20,000 yuan every
year.
</P>
<P>
While they were getting richer, the women broke away from the
old traditional ways of thought of "a woman who has virtue is a
woman who needs no higher learning." In the village, 80 percent of
the women have now joined training courses of various kinds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile's Investment Abroad Totalls 12 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Chile said today its
entrepreneural investments abroad totalled more than 12 billion
U.S. dollars so far this decade.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Investment Committee said the figure was associated
with privatizations in many countries worldwide, and also with the
comparatively small domestic market of Chile -- a country of about
13 million people.
</P>
<P>
Chile's Mercosur (South American Common Market) partners --
Argentine, Brazil, Uruguay and Paraguay -- received 67.6 percent,
or the biggest proportion of Chile's total foreign investments,
the committee said.
</P>
<P>
Argentine alone accounted for 46.6 percent of Chile's
investment abroad.
</P>
<P>
Other markets for Chile's capital flows included Colombia,
Mexico, Panama, Peru and Venezuela and, to a smaller degree, some
European, Asian and African countries as well.
</P>
<P>
Chile's investments abroad focused on the energy, banking,
industrial, financial and commercial areas, said the committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
