<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Rails Install New Switches For Raising Speed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Over 16,000 workers began
installing new switches on the northern section of the
Beijing-Guangzhou Railways to increase speed on this major line.
</P>
<P>
The north-south trunk, together with the Beijing-Shanghai and
Beijing-Harbin lines, will begin to operate at a speed of 140
km-160 km per hour. Previously, the speed has been less than 100
km per hour.
</P>
<P>
Recently, double-deckers have been making trial runs between
Beijing and Beidaihe, a coastal tourist resort in Hebei
Province. And the speed on the Beijing-Guangzhou Railways has been
increased to 180 km per hour on some sections.
</P>
<P>
All major railways in the country have been upgrading parts
such as switches to become faster. The new type of switches are
manufactured by the Shanhaiguan Bridge Plant.
</P>
<P>
Local experts attribute the low speed of the country's rails to
the poor quality of tracks and switches, and the large number of
curves.
</P>
<P>
A couple of years ago, rails, with the length of 1,000 m for a
single piece, were placed on the major lines, while many
elbow-shape spots have been straightened. These improvements allow
for increased speeds.
</P>
<P>
Beginning on April 1, the speed will be raised on these major
lines with Beijing at the center.
</P>
<P>
The railways are China's largest means of transport, carrying
50 percent of the country's passenger transportation and 70
percent of the total cargo shipping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercosur Gets More Foreign Investment in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Members of the South
American Common Market (Mercosur) absorbed 35 percent of the
foreign investments in Latin America last year, the
Inter-AmericanDevelopment Bank said today.
</P>
<P>
The increased investment represented a five percent increase in
the Mercosur share of Latin American investment over the 1991-95
period.
</P>
<P>
The regional trading bloc, comprises Argentina, Brazil,
Paraguay and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
The growth of investments was mainly due to the heavy inflow of
capital to Brazil, 8.1 billion U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Privatization and domestic demand in Argentina and Brazil
appeared to have been the main attractions for the capital inflow
into the two biggest economies in the group.
</P>
<P>
Chief benefitting sectors from the investments included
automobile and automobile parts, food and beverages,
petrochemicals and textiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
