<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Sees Unemployment Rate Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- China's capital city reported an
urban unemployment rate of 0.6 percent last year, the lowest among
the big cities throughout the country, according to the lastest
statistics.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that some 27,600 people were registered
as unemployed in Beijing in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The success should be attributed to the redoubled efforts of
the city's labor department to improve labor policies and
regulations, providing registration and training services for the
jobless people," said an official with the city government.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has set up 187 labor markets and 685 training schools
for the unemployed, while providing labor information and job
recommendation services for both job-seekers and employers.
</P>
<P>
And the city has given a full play to the role of its 5,080
employment service agencies, and encourages laid-off employees to
set up their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
"The number of job-seekers coming in from other parts of the
country was restricted to one million last year," said a leading
official with the city's labor department, adding that this
provided some 40,000 more job opportunities to the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
