<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Prime Minister Visits Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu began his first official visit to Russia on Monday
evening, hoping to persuade Russia to put pressure on Syria to
resume talks with his country.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass news agency said that during his three-day visit,
Netanyahu was expected to meet Russian President Boris Yeltsin,
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov to discuss political expansion and economic cooperation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides were also expected to sign an agreement on
cooperation and mutual assistance in customs operations.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Moscow, Netanyahu told reporters that Russia
remained a great power and would enter the 21st century in this
capacity. Israel believed that developing ties with Russia was
important to his country, and strengthening them was a priority
for Israel.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu wants Moscow to persuade Syria to hold uninterrupted
talks with Israel. He also hopes Russia will stop nuclear
cooperation with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli prime minister will travel to St. Petersburg on
Wednesday, Russia's second-largest city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
