<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Courts in China's Interior Areas to Have Closer Ties With HK Courts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- China's Supreme People's Court,
together with relevant departments, will have closer judicial ties
with courts in Hong Kong and render assistance to each other in
line with provisions of the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) and in accordance with the principle
of "one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
The remark was made today by Ren Jianxin, president of the
Supreme People's Court, at the Fourth Plenary Meeting of the Fifth
Session of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC) in a report
on the work of the Supreme People's Court.
</P>
<P>
The Article 95 of the HKSAR Basic Law stipulates: "The Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region may, through consultations and
in accordance with law, maintain judicial relations with the
judicial organs of other parts of the country, and they may render
assistance to each other."
</P>
<P>
The top judge said that, after China resumes the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1 this year, HKSAR will be
established according to provisions of the Constitution and the
Basic Law of HKSAR, where the policies of "one country, two
systems," "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" and a high degree
of autonomy will be implemented.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR, in accordance with law, will enjoy independent
judicial powers, including that of final adjudication, he said.
Courts in Hong Kong will undoubtedly increase exchanges and ties
with courts in other parts of China after Hong Kong's return, he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the top judge, Chinese courts handled and
concluded 3,831 cases involving Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan in
1996, up by 11.59 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Ren said people's courts have abided by state laws and
regulations and followed the principle of "one country, two
systems" when dealing with cases involving Hong Kong, Macao and
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The people's courts, he said, have safeguarded the legitimate
interests of litigants and impartially handled the cases by
proceeding from the principle of promoting economic and trade
relations between inland areas and Hong Kong and Macao and
promoting cross-strait economic and cultural exchanges and
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Courts Playing Active Role in China's Modernization (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- China's top judge said the
country's judicial system will serve the reform, opening-up and
stability, guarantee and promote the coordinated development of
socialist material and cultural and ethical progress.
</P>
<P>
Ren Jianxin, president of the Supreme People's Court, said
courts at all levels will carry work forward at the behest of Deng
Xiaoping, hold high the great banner of Deng's theory of building
socialism with Chinese characteristics, adhere to the Party's
basic line, and under the leadership of the Party Central
Committee with Jiang Zemin at the core and the supervision of the
people's congress, elevate the judicial work onto a still higher
level.
</P>
<P>
Ren made the remark at the Fourth Plenary Meeting of the
ongoing Fifth Session of the Eighth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the first year of China's Ninth Five-Year Plan
(1996-2000), courts at all levels across China and special courts
such as military and maritime tribunals handled a total of 5.26
million cases of the first instance, and concluded 5.23 million
cases, up 15.82 percent and 15.53 percent respectively from 1995.
And the rises were higher than in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The judicial system played an active role in safeguarding
social stability, guaranteeing the smooth progression of China's
reform and opening-up and its socialist modernization drive, said
Ren.
</P>
<P>
He noted that maintaining social stability is the premise for
the smooth progression of reform and opening-up and economic
development.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, courts across the country, resolutely following the
major policy decisions made the Party Central Committee on
carrying out the "strike hard" campaign to crack down on crimes,
handled 570,000 criminal cases of the first instance and concluded
570,300 cases, a rise of 15.39 percent and 14.97 percent from the
previous year. And 614,000 people were tried and their verdicts
have taken effect.
</P>
<P>
In the "strike hard" campaign and their efforts to crack down
on economic crimes, courts across the country followed the
principle of rendering harsh punishment on criminal and economic
cases in accordance with the law, said Ren.
</P>
<P>
He added the courts also paid attention to the quality of their
work in handling cases, and courts on a higher level increased
their supervision and guidance to those at a lower level, while
major cases were vigorously handled and verdicts made public
promptly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Courts Playing Active Role in China's Modernization (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In their efforts to deal blows to criminal cases that seriously
threaten public security and serious economic cases, Ren observed,
the courts meted out hard blows to violent, gun-related and gang
crimes, drug cases, embezzlement, bribery, misappropriation of
public funds, and crimes that undermine the economic order.
</P>
<P>
The courts also handled a 4.69 million civil, economic,
maritime and administrative cases and concluded 4.66 million cases
last year, up 15.87 percent and 15.6 percent from the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Serious law enforcement, Ren pointed out, is an important part
of building a socialist legal system, and the fundamental
requirements of the Party and the state on judicial activities.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Chinese courts advanced the reform on the methods of
trials, increase supervision over trials and professional
guidance, and increase the execution of verdicts.
</P>
<P>
To guarantee law enforcement and judicial fairness, Ren noted,
Chinese courts has implemented the Law on Judges, and continue
improving the ideological, political, ethical and professional
quality of the judges over the past year.
</P>
<P>
Courts at all levels also dealt harshly with those who took
bribes, or bent the law for the benefit of relatives or friends.
Last year, a total of 1,051 people involved in such cases were
subjected to disciplinary or legal punishment.
</P>
<P>
With the China's resumption of the exercise of its sovereignty
over Hong Kong and the convocation of the 15th National Congress
of the Communist Party of China, Ren noted, 1997 will be an
important year in the history of China's development.
</P>
<P>
The new situation this year set still higher requirements for
the work of the courts, Ren remarked.
</P>
<P>
Main tasks for the courts this year include:
</P>
<P>
-- steadfastly and untiringly carrying out the "strike hard"
campaign;
</P>
<P>
-- continuing to punish harshly criminals involved in
embezzlement and bribery cases;
</P>
<P>
-- re-adjusting economic relations in accordance with the law;
</P>
<P>
-- protecting the legitimate rights and interests of citizens
and legal persons in accordance with the law;
</P>
<P>
-- and further improving the judicial standards and working
hard to improve the competence of the judges.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
