<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Stock Exchange Urged to Find New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The Securities and Exchange
Commission (SEC) has given the Philippine Stock Exchange (PSE) one
month to appoint a new president to replace Vitaliano Nanagas who
was forced to resign last week.
</P>
<P>
SEC Chairman Perfecto Yasay said Monday that until a new
president is appointed, the commission will not decide on the
PSE's standing application for full Self-Regulatory Organization
(SRO) status, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The concern of the commission is the ability of the exchange
to operate as a self-regulatory organization. Definitely, the
commission will not make a decision until Mr. Nanagas has been
replaced," he said.
</P>
<P>
The temporary SRO status the commission granted to the PSE last
December expired on February 28. On the same day, the commission
granted an indefinite extension to allow it to complete its review
of the PSE's requirements and regulatory plans.
</P>
<P>
Nanagas' departure was preceded by widespread discontent among
PSE staff which resulted in the resignation of key officials. Even
PSE Chief Operating Officer Rafael Llave was reportedly planning
to resign due to disagreements with Nanagas' management style.
</P>
<P>
Yasay said the SEC was considering the issuance of clear
guidelines to prevent a similar situation from happening again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
