<HEADLINE> Mercosur Members Report 3.2 Percent Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The members of the South
American Common Market (Mercosur), Argentina, Bolivia, Uruguay and
Paraguay, reported an economic growth of 3.2 percent at the end of
1996 compared with the 1.1 percent reached in 1995.
</P>
<P>
A report by the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) headed by
Enrique Iglesias, a Uruguayan, said that the higher rate of
economic growth was accompanied by a 7.6 percent drop in the
inflationary index in the region.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless the positive results in the economy of this region
contrasted with a greater imbalance in its external accounts,
associated with the progress of Argentina and Brazil, the two
largest partners of the group.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary figures of the IDB document point out that Brazil
could show a four billion U.S. dollar trade deficit and a deficit
of more than 21 billion dollars in its current account.
</P>
<P>
Argentina, in turn, had a current account deficit of about 4.2
billion dollars. The study downplayed a currency devaluation in
either of these two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
