<HEADLINE> Russian Deputy PM: Russia Against NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Russian Deputy Prime Minister Oleg
Lobov said here today Russia opposes NATO's eastward expansion
over concerns for its own security and that of Europe and the
whole world.
</P>
<P>
But he said Russia's opposition would not jeopardize the
expansion of economic cooperation with Bulgaria, one of the
countries applying for NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
During talks in Sofia with Bulgarian Foreign Minister Stoian
Stalev, Lobov stressed that Europe should be united, but Russia
should not be excluded in that process.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his
U.S. counterpart Bill Clinton are expected to seek solutions to
the disputes over NATO's expansion at the Helsinki summit
scheduled for March 20.
</P>
<P>
He added that ongoing negotiations between Russia and NATO were
aimed at reducing the adverse impact of NATO's eastward
enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Lobov said he hoped that the leaders of Bulgaria, one of the
countries applying for NATO membership, would understand Russia's
concerns over NATO's expansion and try to find a way to ease
possible confrontation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
