<HEADLINE> Sino-Japanese Taklimakan Expedition at Halfway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 11 (Xinhua) -- An expedition team composed of six
Chinese and six Japanese have completed half of a risky journey to
cross the Taklimakan Desert in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The trek, which started on February 18, is the second of its
kind. A similar, less arduous, expedition was conducted by a
Sino-British team in 1993 along a different route.
</P>
<P>
The 12 members of the Sino-Japanese joint expedition team,
including a Chinese woman and a Japanese woman, are scientists
from the Xinjiang Biology, Soil and Desert Institute, under the
Chinese Academy of Sciences, and students from the Waseda
University of Japan.
</P>
<P>
The expedition is scheduled to take 40 days and cover 400 km on
foot.  
</P>
