<HEADLINE> Philippine Lower House Pushes for Compromise on Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The leader of the Philippine House
of Representatives has expressed openness to a possible compromise
with the Department of Finance (DOF) on an individual income tax
bill that the Presidential Palace wants to be enacted by May 1.
</P>
<P>
Today's local press quoted House Speaker Jose de Venecia as
saying that a compromise on income tax would be worked out with
the executive branch to enable the country to exit from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The passage of the individual income tax bill, the last part of
the Comprehensive Tax Reform Package, is now the only structural
reform that remains tied to the country's graduation away from the
IMF this June.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia hosted a crucial breakfast meeting Monday with
Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo, Executive Secretary Ruben
Torres and leaders of the House Ways and Means Committee, trying
to draw up the compromise.
</P>
<P>
The House and the DOF are now giving different versions of the
bill. The House tries to raise the exemption level for individuals
to 72,000 pesos (2,748 U.S. dollars) a year and an additional
deduction of 10,000 pesos (381 U.S. dollars) for each of up to
four children in a family.
</P>
<P>
The DOF, however, is batting for an exemption level of 20,000
pesos (763 U.S. dollars) and a 6,500-peso (248 U.S. dollars)
deduction for each dependent child.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia said later on the meeting was intended to "fully
reconcile the conflicting figures" so that the country can fully
exit from the IMF by June 30.
</P>
<P>
He had told President Fidel Ramos that he would expedite the
passing of the individual tax bill, but Senate President Ernesto
Maceda expressed fears that his chamber would not pass the bill on
time due to the delay in the House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
