<HEADLINE> Street Markets in Beijing to Move Indoors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Vendors at Beijing's free markets
will not be free to do business outdoors since the municipal
government plans to move them into indoor markets.
</P>
<P>
The city government plans to eliminate 73 open-air markets
along 255 main avenues by the end of this year in order to make
the capital "tider and traffic will move more freely", according
to a report in today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
All the stands lining Beijing's streets will be removed by the
end of 1999, it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 3,000 square meters for each 10,000 residents will
be set aside for indoor free markets, where vegetables, fruits,
foodstuffs and other cheap commodities for daily use are
available. Each market site will cover at least 1,000 square
meters, the report quoted Tan Zhimin, an official in charge of
environmental sanitation, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Free markets, mainly located in residential areas, have been
playing an important role in providing Chinese urbanities
convenience in daily shopping, apart from the state-owned
department stores, supermarkets and chain stores.
</P>
<P>
However, "some street markets have clogged roadways, choking
traffic and raising the noise level to an irritation point. Street
vendors who cook food are also accused of adding to the city's
pollution," the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Of 847 phone calls and letters from city residents to Tan's
office complaining about environmental problems, 39.4 percent said
they were bothered by the street stands," it noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
