<HEADLINE> Peru's New Car Sales Increase in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Sales of new cars in Peru
increased 19.5 percent to 28,000 in 1996, according to statistics
from the Peruvian Association of Automobile Representatives.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Daewoo and Hyundai car manufacturers joined the
other best-selling trademarks of Toyota, Nissan and Volkswagen
in Peru, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo increased its sales by 25 percent last year, improving
on its 23 percent market share the previous year. In 1996, the
Daewoo company sold 3,671 Tico cars and 2,412 Racer vehicles.
Hyundai reported similar increases in its local sales last year.
</P>
<P>
The Toyota brand maintained its leading position with a
34.9 percent share of the market at the end of 1996. Nissan had
a market share of 20.6 percent. 
