<HEADLINE> ASEAN, China to Speed up Formation of Business Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN and China have agreed to
speed up the establishment of the ASEAN-China Business Council to
exploit market potentials in the two regions with a total
population of 1.8 billion, an official said.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and
Industry for Chinese Committee Chris Walean said last night after
a meeting between the ASEAN Chamber of Commerce and Industry and
China's Council for the Promotion of International Trade (CCPIT),
that the agreement would open great business opportunities for
ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the ASEAN-China Business Council could hopefully be
established next month when the International Chamber of Commerce
and Industry meets in Shanghai, China.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand
and Vietnam,
</P>
<P>
Trade between the ASEAN and China reached 20 billion U.S.
dollars in 1995, 40 percent higher than 1994.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on trade relations between Indonesia and China, he
said opportunities were wide open for the two countries to
increase their trade volume.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, bilateral trade between China
and Indonesia reached 3.78 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Chinese investment in Indonesia reached nearly 200
million dollars. Compared with Malaysia and Thailand, the figure
was relatively small, he said.
</P>
<P>
The smaller amount of Chinese investment in Indonesia was due
to the fact that most Chinese investors still could not make
maximum use of the facilities provided by the Indonesian
government, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added it took months for Chinese investors to get their visa
from the Indonesian government.  
</P>
