<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Riders and Teams Fined for Positive EPO Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Three riders, who were found
positive in EPO test before the first stage of the Paris-Nice
cycling race, were fined on Monday.
</P>
<P>
EPO, or erythropoietin, a drug produced to treat kidney
disease, is used to increase oxygen-carrying red blood cell levels
which enhance endurance.
</P>
<P>
Frenchman Erwan Mentheour and Italian pair Luca Colombo and
Mauro Santaromita all submitted blood samples which showed red
blood cell levels in excess of the 50 percent limit -- they were
fined 1,000 Swiss francs (480 U.S. dollars) while their teams were
fined 40,000 Swiss francs by the International Cycling Union
(UCI), the sports' governing body.
</P>
<P>
High red blood cell levels, which thicken the blood, can induce
heart attacks and an official statement from the race jury
announced that the trio had been "declared temporarily unfit to
take part in sport".
</P>
<P>
The three cyclists are the first victims of new UCI rules
allowing it to suspend cyclists for two weeks if they fail the
test. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0292 </DOCNO>
