<HEADLINE> European Shares End at New Records on Strong Dow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- All the three major stock markets
in Europe ended at record closing highs Monday, fueled by Wall
Street's sustained gains and domestic economic outlook.
</P>
<P>
British shares in London closed 17.1 points stronger at
4,437.4, the fifth consecutive record closing high, after having
touched an all-time record of 4,440.8 earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
A firm start to trading on Wall Street helped London to sustain
its advance in thin volumes during afternoon trade, but traders
said that there were some signs of pre-election jitters appearing.
</P>
<P>
The market also received a massive vote of confidence from Bank
of England governor Eddie George who predicted earlier today that
Britain will hit its 2.5 percent inflation target, suggesting to
dealers that the chance of an early rise in interest rates had
receded quite significantly.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, shares also closed at a new record high, lifted
by the Dow's Friday strong rally, a stable, though slightly lower,
dollar and firmer bonds prices, with the DAX-30 index 59.87 points
higher at 3,436.07.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, stocks finished just above the
2,700-level, up 0.93 points at 2,709.21, still a new record
closing for the fourth session running, supported also by the
Dow's strong surge last Friday.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index of leading British shares closed 17.1
points higher at 4,437.4. The Frankfurt DAX-30 index ended up
59.87 points at 3,436.07. In Paris, the CAC-40 index finished 0.93
points stronger at 2,709.21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
