<HEADLINE> Burns: Chinese Naval Vessels Visit to U.S. Very Important </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Spokesman of U.S. Department
of State Nicholas Burns today described the visit of Chinese naval
vessels to U.S. ports as "both newsworthy and very important".
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the press briefing, Burns said the Chinese vessels
are destroyers and oilers, which are on a training course in the
Eastern Pacific.
</P>
<P>
This is "significant" because this is "the first port visit by
these types of ship ever to the continental United States since
the founding of the People's republic of China back in 1949," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The visit "reflects the fact that we've got engage with the
Chinese militarily as well as politically and economically," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"It's a very important step forward for the United States and
China, and it begins this week," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that during Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian's
visit to the United States last December, both sides "agreed that
we ought to reengage on a military-to-military relationship."
</P>
<P>
Burns pointed out particularly that the Chinese naval vessels
visit to the United States also demonstrates "the reemergence of a
U.S.-China military-to-military dialogue."
</P>
<P>
According to Burns, the three Chinese naval ships arrived in
Pearl Harbor on March 9, and are scheduled to leave on March 13.
They will visit San Diego at U.S. naval base in California from
March 21 to 25.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese naval training ship visited Pear Harbor in April
1989. 
</P>
</TEXT>
