<HEADLINE> US Says Trial of Bosnian War Crimes Marks Step Forward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States said today
that the trial of Bosnian Muslims for war crimes allegedly
committed against Bosnian Serbs marks a significant step forward.
</P>
<P>
The International War Crimes Tribunal, which is based in the
Hague, the Netherlands, began today its first trial for war crimes
allegedly committed against Bosnian Muslims. Three of the
indictees are Bosnian Muslims and one is a Croatian.
</P>
<P>
"Their trail today marks a significant step forward for the War
Crimes Tribunal," U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"And it says a lot about the impartiality of that tribunal," he
added. Bosnian Serbs have complained that the tribunal only deals
with crimes committed by Serbs.
</P>
<P>
Burns urged Bosnian Serbs to give in those who are accused of
war crimes during the civil war to the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
He said that the trial says a lot about the Bosnian
government's willingness to extradite to the Hague its own
citizens who are Muslims.
</P>
<P>
"And it stands in stark contrast to the attitude and behavior
of the Bosnian Serbs, and...the Croatian government, which by and
large have failed to adhere to their Dayton commitments in turning
over indicted war criminals for prosecution at the Hague," Burns
added.
</P>
<P>
According to the Dayton accord signed Serbs, Muslims and
Croats, the parties should turn over the indicted war criminals to
the Hague for trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Deports U.S. Diplomat for Economic Spying, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Germany has for the first time in
the postwar era ordered a U.S. diplomat to leave the country on
charge of economic espionage, the German weekly newsmagazine Der
Spiegel reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to Der Spiegel's account, a CIA agent working under
diplomatic cover tried to recruit a senior official of Germany's
Economics Ministry in order to obtain classified information on
high technology projects.
</P>
<P>
The official who was approached reported the matter to
Germany's counterespionage agency, the Federal Office for the
Protection of the Constitution, which demanded that the diplomat
leave the country.
</P>
<P>
The news weekly said the U.S. diplomat, whom it did not
identify, had already left Germany. In order to avoid any
disruption in bilateral relations, the affair was handled by
intelligence agencies of both nations instead of through formal
diplomatic channels, Der Spiegel said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns reportedly
declined to comment on the issue Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
