<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls U.N. Resolution "Ill-advised" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton,
in his defense of a veto to a U.N. Security Council's resolution
condemning Israel's housing plan in Arab east Jerusalem, said on
Monday that any kind of such a resolution was "ill-advised" in
resolving thorny issues concerning the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He made the argument at a joint news conference at the White
House following his talks with visiting Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, who accused Israel of flagrant violation of its agreement
with the Palestinians on the final Status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told reporters that he felt the resolution of the
Security Council was "ill-advised" because the United States does
not want the Security Council to impose any resolution on the
peace process, as the United States intended to be exclusive peace
broker in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We can never achieve peace through U.N. Security Council
resolutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Jerusalem issue is a disputed one, as the Arab
world see the building of a Jewish neighborhood in east Jerusalem
is "a settlement and therefor a violation," while the Israelis
believe that is "already part of their territory."
</P>
<P>
the area that the Israeli government is going to build 6,500
Jewish homes is called Abu Ghenaim or Har Homa, which was captured
by Israel during the 1967 Middle East war. Israel has henceforth
declared the entire city of Jerusalem as an undivided one and will
be its capital, even though the international community, including
the United States, have refused to recognized its claim.
</P>
<P>
Clinton admitted, however, the Israeli move to build a Jewish
neighborhood in east Jerusalem "would not build confidence, would
not be conducive to negotiations; would be seen by the
Palestinians and others as an attempt to precondition some of the
final status issues."
</P>
<P>
His remarks go with what he said was "build mistrust" between
the Israelis and Palestinians when he met Palestinians leader
Yasser Arafat last Monday, but contradicted U.S. veto in the U.N.
Security Council and his defense of the veto.
</P>
<P>
He shared with Mubarak with a view that Jerusalem should be
"part of the final status negotiations".
</P>
<P>
"Everything surrounding Jerusalem is of immense emotional,
political and religious significance to all the parties involved
here. That's why they wisely put it as a final status issue," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said the Israel's housing plan has brought more
"difficulties and complications", which could only "make the
peace process a fragile and vulnerable one."
</P>
<P>
"The issue of Jerusalem is as sensitive to Moslems and to
Christians as it is to Jews. Hence, the rights and sentiments of
all these people should be fully respected..... We view such
actions (of building the Jewish homes in east Jerusalem) as
flagrant violations that would not serve any useful purpose," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who arrived in Washington on Saturday for three-day
visit, said earlier that it was a regret that the United States
should have vetoed the U.N. Security Council's resolution and it
would cost the United States credibility as a peace broker in the
Arab world.
</P>
<P>
He urged Clinton to use his influence to pressure Israel to
reverse its decision of housing construction.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak also called for the negotiations resumed on the Syrian
and Lebanese track so that there would be a complete peace in the
region.
</P>
<P>
He said Syrian President Hafez Assad was "positively inclined"
to reopen the Syrian-Israeli peace negotiations, which was
suspended a year ago.
</P>
<P>
"He reiterated serious commitment to a just and comprehensive
peace settlement on the basis of Madrid formula. He believes...
that the talks should be resumed from the point where the parties
had left off a year ago," he conveyed the message to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
As Mubarak and Clinton discussed the Middle East peace process
issues, Palestinians clashed with Israeli soldiers in the West
Bank with several Palestinians injured by troops who used clubs
and guns to beat back about 100 Arabs who tried to stop workers
from opening a road for Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
The clash was the first serious outbreak of Arab-Israeli
violence since Yasser Arafat spurned an Israeli decision to hand
over another nine percent of the West Bank to Palestinian
self-rule in the first stage of the Israeli pullout from the rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said Israel only intended to give up 30 percent of the
land in the West Bank rural areas in its three stages of pullout
while he demanded 90 percent of the land. He blamed on Monday that
Isreal's decision on pullout of its troops from the rural areas
had created a "real crisis." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
