<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US FTC Moves to Block Staples-Office Depot Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Trade
Commission (FTC) voted today to block a merger of the two largest
U.S. office supply retailers in a bid to prevent them from
monopolying the market.
</P>
<P>
The FTC said that it would seek a court order to prevent
Staples Inc. from acquiring Office Depot Inc.
</P>
<P>
The two largest office supply retailers had announced last year
that they decided to merger into one firm which would have
approximately 1,000 superstores in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
In raising its objections by a vote of 4-1 today, the FTC said
the acquisition of 4 billion dollars would allow the combined firm
to control prices for the sale of office supplies in various
cities throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
"The fact is, that in those communities where Staples faces
competition from Office Depot, prices are significantly lower than
where it does not," said William J. Baer, director of the FTC's
bureau of competition.
</P>
<P>
A preliminary court injunction would prevent the merger from
going forward while the FTC pursues its investigation.
</P>
<P>
At present, the two companies own a combined 1,124 stores in
the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
Todd Krasnow, Staples' executive vice president for marketing
said today that Staples will "vigorously contest" the FTC's
intervention. He said that the deal was pro-competitive and will
result in lower prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
