<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. States Alleged Not to Protect Female Inmates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Justice Department today
alleged that Arizona and Michigan fail to protect female inmates
from rapes and sexual assaults by prison guards and staff,
according to an Associated Press report.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department, in separate lawsuits filed in U.S.
District Court in Phoenix and Detroit, alleged that conditions in
state-run prisons violate the federal Civil Rights of
Institutionalized Persons Act of 1980.
</P>
<P>
At the Arizona Center for Women and at state prison facilities
in Alhambra, Perryville and Tucson, female inmates have been
subjected to sexual misconduct and unlawful invasion of privacy,
including prurient viewing during showering, toileting and
dressing, the department charged.
</P>
<P>
The department also said that female inmates at Michigan's
Scott and Crane correctional facilities have suffered the similar
sexual misconduct.
</P>
<P>
The department said that it began to investigate the cases at
prison facilities in two state in 1994 and 1995, but the two
states did not provide cooperation.
</P>
<P>
They either refused to allow Justice investigators access to
its prisons and would not negotiate to resolve the allegations or
refused to allow Justice attorneys to interview prison staff
members and prisoners about the complaints, the department said.
</P>
<P>
Both lawsuits sought court orders requiring the states to
protect female inmates from rapes, sexual assaults and other
improper sexual contact by the staff; to ensure that inmates and
staff do not engage in sexual relations; and that women inmates
fare not viewed in a prurient manner when showering, changing
clothes and using toilets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Report Says Croatia Failed to Protect Serbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 10 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. report on the human
rights situation in Croatia said on Monday that Zagreb had made
little progress in its treatment of minority Serbs since a similar
report was submitted three months ago.
</P>
<P>
The report, which was issued under the name of U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, also said that Croatia, despite
public statements to the contrary, had failed to arrest suspected
war criminals indicted by the Hague-based tribunal on the former
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. tribunal has indicted some 74 suspects -- 53 Serbs, 18
Croats and three Moslems. But most remain at large.
</P>
<P>
Up to 200,000 Serbs fled when Zagreb's troops recaptured the
Serb-dominated Krajina region in two swift offensives in mid-1995.
Only a few Serbs remained in the area and about 14,000 have been
allowed to return.
</P>
<P>
"Croatian Serbs continue to live in conditions of serious
insecurity," the report said. "Incidents of looting and harassment
remain common. Croatian police authorities are ineffective in
restoring security"
</P>
<P>
"There remains strong grounds for concern that the government
is withholding its full cooperation," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Croatia refused to accept the U.N. allegation, saying that the
incidents against Serbs should be viewed as a natural crime rate
rather than human rights violations and that all Croatians were
paying the price of years of warfare.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
