<HEADLINE> Subdued Output Prices Ease UK Rate Rise Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Britain's factory gate price
inflation remained subdued and at the lowest level for over a
decade in February, keeping pressures on an interest rate rise at
bay, official figures showed Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics (ONS) said today that
producer output prices were unchanged compared with January and
1.3 percent up year-on-year, the lowest level since August 1986.
</P>
<P>
Core output prices, which exclude food, drink, tobacco and
petrol products, rose 0.1 percent on January and 0.5 percent on
the year, the lowest annual gain since 1967.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, producer input prices, or the costs of raw
materials, fell 0.5 percent from January to February, giving an
annual fall of 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government welcomed the "outstanding" figures, saying the
data were proof that its economic policies were working and
Britain had an unclouded outlook for retail prices for the next
few months.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the figures suggested that there were little
need for an interest rate rise as there were few inflationary
pressures in the economy at present.
</P>
<P>
Economists believed that lower oil prices and the strength of
sterling helped drag input prices down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
