<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastern Africa Advances in Regional Coop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The East African Cooperation
(EAC) has made achievements in the identification of the priority
for cooperation in political, security, economic, social,
cultural, legal and judicial spheres.
</P>
<P>
In an interview issued today by the East African weekly, EAC
Executive Secretary Francis Muthaura said that "progress has been
impressive by any standards" over the past year in the area of
cooperation among Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The currencies of the three countries now become convertible
in the whole EAC region.
</P>
<P>
He said during the year, the EAC Secretariat, set up on March
14 1996, held no less than 30 sectoral meetings aimed at
harmonizing policies of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
On the easing of the movement of people and goods, the three
EAC members have agreed on a travel document which is expected to
be launched in April this year.
</P>
<P>
The movement of people and goods among the states are "much
easier today than before", although there is still a lot to be
done, said the EAC chief.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the three eastern African countries also have
signed a memorandum of understanding on the establishment of the
East African Securities Regulatory Authority.
</P>
<P>
Revenue Authorities of Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda have regular
meetings to facilitate the development of convergence of fiscal
policies, he added.
</P>
<P>
In the energy sector, the EAC projects include the immediate
inter-connection of the national grids for turning them into a
single East African network and power supply to border towns from
the three countries' power administrations.
</P>
<P>
Muthaura added that the EAC Development Strategy (1997-2000),
a master plan for the integration of the eastern African region
in political, economic and social fields, is expected to be
launched in April this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
