<DOCNO> XIE19970311.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supporters for Liberia's Detained Faction Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Supporters of Liberia's former
faction leader Alhaji Kromah today shut shops and suspended
businesses in solidarity to protest the detainment of Kromah on
charge of illegal possession of weapons.
</P>
<P>
A TV report said tonight that Kromah's fellow Mandingoes,
including gas and petroleum dealers and commercial vehicle
operators, stopped their business in a bid to slow down the pace
of concerned moves in Monrovia, the capital of Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The protest went ahead despite the warning from the Moslem
community that it could worsen the crisis stimulated by the
arrest of Alhaji Kromah, the report said.
</P>
<P>
A radio broadcast in Monrovia today urged all Mandingoes not
to treat the arrest of Kromah as a witch hunt against them.
</P>
<P>
Today's protest came after the West African peace-keeping
force (ECOMOG) reportedly raided the homes of close relatives of
Kromah in the eastern suburbs of Monrovia on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A cousin of Alhaji Kromah, who is the chief of staff of the
armed forces of Liberia, said Kromah's ECOMOG bodyguards have
been withdrawn after the detainment of Kromah when three trucks
of arms were found in his home last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kromah has since been under house arrest, with telephone lines
cut off and activities into his home blocked by tanks.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG, which oversees the Liberian peace process, has
announced it would treat any one caught with weapons as criminal
after the conclusion of voluntary disarmament for the former
rival factions at the end of January this year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, ECOMOG Commander Major-General Victor Malu said
Kromah would be handed over to the civil police for possible
prosecution after investigations are completed.
</P>
<P>
Liberia's Independent press today also called for the
prosecution of Kromah, who has resigned from the post of
vice-chairman of the ruling Council of State to run for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
However, General Moses Dar argued the arms discovery had been
recorded by ECOMOG before the deadline date but ECOMOG had not
turned up to pack the arms.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG's action was a "scheme to destroy Alhaji Kromah
politically, given the level of momentum in his effort to
organize a political party, transforming a military organization
into a major political organization," he charged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
