<HEADLINE> UK, US Share Prices Forecast to Slide: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Fund managers in Britain are
pessimistic about the prospects for stock markets in London and
New York despite the recent new records in share prices, according
to a survey of investment intentions for stockbrokers Merrill
Lynch today.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which covered 67 institutions managing more than
900 billion pounds (1440 billion US dollars), shows that sellers
of British shares outweigh buyers by seven percent while for the
American market, the balance between sellers and buyers is 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
Most managers forecast a fall in London and New York shares
over the next three months, with British interest rates to be
higher in a year's time and companies earnings growth falling as
the main factors.
</P>
<P>
On average, companies earnings growth is expected to be 8.6
percent this year, instead of an expectation of 10 percent made in
October 1996.
</P>
<P>
The strength of sterling, which has gained around 16 percent on
a trade-weighted basis since last August, is said to have made
investors lower their forecasts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
