<HEADLINE> Safety Fears over BA's New Long-haul Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- British Airways (BA) has withdrawn
its new multi-million pound superjets from long-haul routes to
America because of safety fears.
</P>
<P>
Three Boeing 777 model BA were switched to shorter-haul
European and Middle East destinations "as a precaution", according
to an announcement by BA released here today.
</P>
<P>
Until the problems are solved, engineers decided the
twin-engined jets should be used only on shorter routes so that
they would be closer to an airport if an emergency landing became
necessary, a BA spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Problems have been found with the lubrication of the gear box
bearings of the three aircraft with General Electric engines.
</P>
<P>
A BA pilot said: "The problem is that the triple seven has only
two engines. I don't want to be stuck in the middle of the
Atlantic with only one."
</P>
<P>
The BA spokesman said: "The problem has been identified and
parts are being brought in from the States.
</P>
<P>
"To us, safety is paramount, so the three B model 777s were
withdrawn from the transatlantic flights as a precaution," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Aviation expert John Loader said that the airline deserved
credit for the decision. "It's a sensible and correct thing to do
but it will be commercially disastrous," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
